om IMF managing director Christine Lagarde:</p><blockquote><p>\"Greece has made tremendous efforts to implement wide-ranging painful measures over the past two years, in the midst of a deep economic recession and a difficult social environment. The fiscal deficit has been reduced markedly and competitiveness has gradually improved. However, the challenges confronting Greece remain significant, with a large competitiveness gap, a high level of public debt, and an undercapitalized banking system.</p><p>\"The new Fund-supported program will enable Greece to address these challenges while remaining in the Eurozone. The program focuses on restoring competitiveness and growth, fiscal sustainability, and financial stability. The authorities are fully committed to these ambitious objectives and stand ready to take any additional measures as may be necessary. The successful debt exchange operation, debt relief and long-term support from Greece's European partners, and the commitment of the major Greek political parties to program objectives and policies provide important assurances for the new program.</p><p>\"Greece's priority is to undertake competitiveness-enhancing structural reforms. The government's bold labor market measures will play a crucial role in this regard, complemented by measures to liberalize professions and product markets, improve the business environment, and privatize state-owned assets.</p><p>\"Significant further fiscal adjustment is necessary to put debt on a sustainable downward trajectory. Reaching a primary surplus of 4½ percent of GDP by 2014 will require politically difficult cuts in government spending, as well as decisive measures to address tax evasion. It is important that the adjustment be both fair and sustainable, through strengthening the core social safety net and tax collection efforts.</p><p>\"Securing financial sector stability and depositor confidence is also a priority. The program secures liquidity support for Greek banks, and provides funds for their recapitalization, alongside incentives to preserve private ownership. The resolution framework and the governance of oversight agencies have been strengthened to ensure appropriate use of public funds and safeguard against conflicts of interest.</p><p>\"Risks to the program remain exceptionally high, and there is no room for slippages. Full and timely implementation of the planned adjustment—alongside broad-based public support and support from Greece's European partners—will be critical to success. The euro area leaders have reiterated their commitment to provide adequate support to Greece during the life of the program and beyond until it has regained market access, provided that Greece fully complies with the requirements and objectives of the adjustment program.\"</p></blockquote><!-- Block 34 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408749'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2010/04/09/recap2.gif' alt='Live blog: recap' width='40' height='40' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">6.03pm:</span> Time to knock this blog on the head for the day (unless there are any exciting developments this evening, in which case it might roar back into life).</p><p><strong>Here's a closing summary:</strong></p><p>• <strong>The International Monetary Fund has agreed to extend Greece a €28bn loan over the next four years.</strong> The IMF will <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating?commentpage=4#block-26\">give Athens €1.65bn straight away</a>.<br />• <strong>The EU taskforce said Greece was making progress to reform its economy.</strong> <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating?commentpage=4#block-25\">Horst Reichenbach. head of the taskforce, admitted there was a huge amount still to do</a> but listed several areas of progress.<br />• <strong>Evangelos Venizelos, the outgoing Greek finance minister, indicated Greece will return to growth in 2013.</strong> The next leader of the Pasok party insisted that <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating?commentpage=4#block-19\">structural reforms will bring the country to a better future</a>.<br />• <strong>Standard &amp; Poor's said it would raise Greece out of selective default in April.</strong> The new rating, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating?commentpage=4#block-28\">of CCC</a>, is lower than that of Fitch.<br />• <strong>Fitch's decision to cut the UK's credit rating outlook to negative hung over the City today.</strong> Economists believe the move means there is <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating?commentpage=4#block-3\">no chance of George Osborne announcing any unfunded giveaways in next week's Budget</a>.<br />• <strong>It was a mixed day for Ireland.</strong> An oil company <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating?commentpage=4#block-11\">struck black gold</a> off the coast of Cork, but the country's central banker called for <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating?commentpage=4#block-17\">a more 'proactive' approch to repossessions</a>. Finance minister Michael Noonan also pledged to push for progress on <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating?commentpage=4#block-23\">the sticky issue of its promissory notes</a>.</p><p>I'm off tomorrow, so my colleagues will be a'blogging. Good night, and a good weekend, to all.</p><!-- Block 33 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408750'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2010/5/5/1273067757521/Live-blog---Greece-flag-001.jpg' alt='Live blog - Greece flag' width='60' height='40' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">5.52pm:</span> Some late news in from Athens where our correspondent <strong>Helena Smith</strong> says technocrat prime minister <strong>Lucas Papademos</strong> has been holding talks with Greece's central bank chairman <strong>Giorgos Provopoulos</strong> over the recapitalisation of the country's banking sector.</p><p>The discussions are further proof that Greek authorities are determined to move ahead with pumping cash into the market place through small firms - a vital next step according to EU task force chief <strong>Horst Reichenbach</strong> (see our report <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating?commentpage=4#block-25\">from 3.55pm</a>)</p><!-- Block 32 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">5.25pm:</span> Fitch just announced that it has revised the Bank of England's credit rating outlook to negative, and affirmed its AAA rating.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408751'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2008/08/15/bank460x276.jpg' alt='A bus passes by the Bank of England' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Readers: Imagine a joke about waiting ages for a credit rating change..... Photograph: Peter Macdiarmid/Getty Images</figcaption></figure><p>That follow's last night's announcement <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating#block-3\">about Britain's sovereign credit rating</a>. Typically, a change to a country's credit rating has a knock-on impact on its financial sector. After all, it would be odd for a central bank to have a better credit rating than the government that ultimately stands behind it.</p><!-- Block 31 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">5.20pm:</span> Dow Jones Newswires reports that the IMF decision to approve Greece's aid loan (see <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating#block-26\">4.02pm</a>) was not unanimous. Instead, it says, Brazil's representative abstained from the decision in protest....</p><!-- Block 30 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">5.00pm:</span> For appearance's sake, we should record that the <strong>FTSE 100</strong> closed 4 points lower at 5940.</p><p>It was a quiet day in most European markets, with the German <strong>Dax</strong> and the Italian <strong>FTSE MIB</strong> the best performers (both closing 0.9% higher).</p><!-- Block 29 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">4.53pm:</span> Video highlights of a debate on the future of the eurozone held yesterday in the City are now online <a href=\"http://www.openeurope.org.uk/Article/Page/en/LIVE?id=8538\">here</a>.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/14/eurozone-crisis-markets-rally-greece#block-18\">As we blogged yesterday</a>, it involved <strong>Julian Callow</strong> of <strong>Barclays Capital</strong>, <strong>Megan Greene</strong> of <strong>Roubini Global Economics</strong> and <strong>Raoul Ruparel</strong> of <strong>Open Europe</strong>. Worth a watch.</p><!-- Block 28 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">4.35pm:</span> Another development: <strong>Standard &amp; Poor's has announced that it will rate Greece's new bonds at CCC, once the bond swap is concluded.</strong></p><p>Currently S&amp;P has Greece in <strong>Selective Default</strong>, but it confirmed that it will assign a rating of <strong>CCC</strong> (three notches above Default) once the outstanding foreign-issued bonds have been swapped in April.</p><p>That's a lower rating than Fitch, which <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/13/eurozone-crisis-greek-deal-spain-austerity\">announced on Tuesday it would rate Greece as <strong>B-</strong></a>.</p><p>Here's S&amp;P's explanation:</p><blockquote><p>The 'CCC' rating assigned to Greece's new bonds is constrained by our view of Greece's uncertain economic growth prospects, what we consider a weakening political consensus for ambitious and largely unpopular reforms, and the still-large external and fiscal debt burdens, even after the debt restructuring is concluded. The rating also reflects our view of the sizable implementation risks to the ambitious fiscal consolidation targets under the second financial assistance program for Greece. Our rating on Greece is supported by the increased average maturity of the central government debt stock and the reduction in debt servicing costs as a result of the exchange; and by the recapitalization of the banks, which we believe should help to maintain domestic depositor confidence.</p><p>These factors have, in our view, reduced the risk of a second debt restructuring in the immediate future. Our recovery rating of '4' for Greece remains unchanged, indicating an estimated 30%-50% recovery by bondholders.</p></blockquote><!-- Block 27 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408752'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/5/12/1305203064788/Live-blog-news-flash-001.jpg' alt='Live blog: news flash newsflash' width='40' height='40' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">4.27pm:</span> More breaking news -- <strong>Standard &amp; Poor's has just reiterated its negative outlook on the US credit rating.</strong></p><p>S&amp;P, which famously cut America from AAA to AA+ last August, added that it was improbable any economic improvement would bring back America's triple-A rating anytime soon.</p><p>US shares have responded by, er, heading higher – with the S&amp;P 500 index crashing through the 1,400 mark for the first time since June 2008.</p><!-- Block 26 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408753'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/5/12/1305203064788/Live-blog-news-flash-001.jpg' alt='Live blog: news flash newsflash' width='40' height='40' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">4.02pm:</span> Breaking news from the International Monetary Fund – <strong>it has approved the €28bn loan to Greece</strong>.</p><p>Here's the official statement, confirming that the IMF will pay its share of Greece' second aid package.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The Executive Board of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) today approved a four-year SDR [special drawing rights] 23.8 billion (about €28 billion, or US$36.7 billion) arrangement under the Extended Fund Facility (EFF) for Greece in support of the authorities' economic adjustment program.</p><p>The approval allows for an immediate disbursement of SDR 1.4 bilion (about €1.65 billion, or US$2.2 billion). The EFF arrangement entails exceptional access to IMF resources, amounting to 2,159% of Greece's quota.</p></blockquote><p>A fuller statement should follow.</p><p>That's the final piece of the Greek bailout jigsaw in place. I think the Greek parliament needs to give its approval, but there's no chance of that not happening.</p><p>And here's <a href=\"http://www.imf.org/external/np/exr/facts/sdr.htm\">an explainer</a> of how Special Drawing Rights work.</p><!-- Block 25 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">3.55pm:</span> As promised, here's our report on today's new conference held by the EU's taskforce to Greece, from <strong>Helena Smith</strong>:</p><blockquote><p>Horst Reichenbach, the head of the EU body tasked with rebuilding Greece has the demeanour of a salesman. In fact it is easy to imagine him in an Audi showroom singing the praises of the company's latest model \"it's good, it's dependable, the best of German.\"</p><p>But while keen to always appear exceptionally polite, the soft-spoken German is not into sales pitches or any kind of patter at all. When he speaks he weighs his words carefully. And when he opens his mouth in Greece what comes out is exceptionally measured.<br /> <br />Such attributes were on FULL display this afternoon as the European Commission mandarin spoke at length about the priorities of the task force in Greece – a country with a \"very specific and particular situation.\"<br />A former vice president of the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, Reichenbach who has worked at the European commission for 30 years, has almost overnight become one of the most powerful men in Greece. With growth now the name of the game if the nation is to survive its worst crisis in modern times, Greeks have found themselves, increasingly, hanging from his every word.</p></blockquote><p>But seated before a Greek and EU flag in the grand surroundings of Athens' Zappeion conference centre today Reichenbach was at pains to deny he was taking over the country. The task force was there, he said,  because the Greeks had asked for help.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408754'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2012/3/15/1331828297034/Horst-Reichenbach-speaks--007.jpg' alt='Horst Reichenbach, speaks during a press conference in Athens on March 15, 2012.' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Horst Reichenbach today. Photograph: Louisa Gouliamaki/AFP/Getty Images</figcaption></figure><p>Here's how <strong>Reichenbach</strong> described the taskforce:</p><p>\"It is a concrete contribution of EU solidarity to Greece. It was created at the request of the former prime minister George Papandreou to assist Greece in absorbing available EU funding … the starting point is always Greek ownership. The Greeks have to present ideas for technical assistance to achieve objectives.\"  </p><p><strong>Helena</strong> continues:</p><blockquote><p>Because Greece \"found it easier\" to enact legislation but was not so good at implementing it, he and his staff had, however, devised a \"road map.\" The taskforce would also be sending in experts (mostly French and German) to overhaul the country's public administration now seen as the biggest barrier to the reforms required to revive the Greek economy and make it more competitive. For the first time civil servants would be evaluated \"as is common practice in other EU states.\"<br />\"A lot remains to be done. There is too much red tape and administrative barriers … for example customs controls for exports take 20 days when the European average is 10 days.\" <br />But, he added, referring to last week's historic restructuring of Greek debt, \"the PSI and second adjustment program have eliminated some of the uncertainty hanging over Greek developments. Now we have the possibility to have a new start on a much more solid basis.\"<br />Another priority was to boost market liquidity by financing small and medium sized enterprises (SME's) – traditionally the Greek economy's lifeblood -- which the German acknowledged had been \"in extremely short supply.\"<br />A total of €4bn was available in the form of grants and loans.  \"We now have to see how this potential can be used,\" he insisted.   <br />\"The second great task of the task force is the technical assistance [it can provide] in favour of structural reforms. An unprecedented amount of assistance has been made available from 16 member states,\" he continued, pointing out EU countries that economically may not be so strong themselves had graciously accepted \"to contribute.\"         <br />There were other areas where Greece could also improve, starting with the modernization of the health system, e-governance and re-organisation of the judicial system also seen as a major obstacle to business in Greece. It was urgent, too, that the Greek banking sector was recapitalized in order to ensure that funds could be disbursed to their \"final destination in the real economy that is SME's.\"<br />In fact there was almost no area of life that would not be affected by the special EU task force.</p></blockquote><p>So was Herr Reichenbach afraid that he or any of his staff might be open to \"abuse or insult\" in Greece, one reporter asked. After all the recent fuss over Berlin's alleged plan to appoint a permanent EU commissioner in Athens it was not unreasonable to think that trouble could lie ahead.</p><p>Helena, though, reports that he merely smiled before launching into Euro-speak about \"mandates and technical assistance\", and smiling again.</p><!-- Block 24 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">3.27pm:</span> The euro has climbed higher today, up around half a cent to $1.3078 against the US dollar.</p><p>That's despite <strong>Lorenzo Bini Smagh</strong>, a former member of the European Central Bank, predicting this morning that Portugal and Ireland will both need fresh financial support.</p><p>Bini Smagh argued (as many have before) that Portugal may not be able to return to the financial markets today, and would need a second aid package worth €100bn. Ireland, he added, would need another €80bn.</p><p><strong>David Song</strong>, currency analyst at <strong>DailyFX</strong>, warned that fears over Ireland and Portugal would push the euro lower in the weeks ahead:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>We are likely to see the single currency face additional headwinds over the near-term as the sovereign debt crisis continues to drag on investor confidence....</p><p>The heightening risk for contagion instills a bearish forecast for the Euro versus the US dollar as the fundamental outlook for the euro-area remains weak.</p></blockquote><!-- Block 23 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408755'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Politics/Pix/pictures/2011/12/15/1323937941786/Michael-Noonan-004.jpg' alt='Michael Noonan' width='220' height='132' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Michael Noonan, the Irish finance minister. Photograph: Haydn West/PA</figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">3.06pm:</span> Ireland's finance minister <strong>Michael Noonan</strong> has touched on an important issue that I've rather neglected above the line -- ongoing negotiations over Irish promissory notes.</p><p>Around €30bn of these promissory notes (a kind of IOU with regular interest payments attached) were issued by the Irish government in 2008 to finance the bailout of Anglo Irish Bank (one of the lenders crushed by the financial crisis). With interest included, the cost of the notes will reach €47bn by the time Ireland has paid them off in 2031.</p><p>Dublin now argues that the burden of the notes is too great, and it should be allowed to exchange them for loans from the European Financial Stability Fund, repayable over at least 30 years at a lower interest rate. Europe, though, refuses to accept this -- and says Ireland should instead pay its next interest rate payment, worth €3.1bn.</p><p>And thus there has been deadlock. The FT (<a href=\"http://blogs.ft.com/the-world/2012/03/qa-irish-promises-and-promissory-notes/#axzz1pCOxwaGR\">which also wrote a good Q&amp;A on this yesterday</a>) published an leader comment today urging the EU to accept Dublin's request, and <strong>Let Ireland Succeed</strong>.</p><p>So back to Noonan. On a trip to Paris today, he said he is hopeful of a deal by the end of 2012 that would keep the new interest rate \"quite low\". Noonan told reporters that:</p><blockquote><p>We would like if it was finished in calendar 2012. With the kind of arrangements we have in mind, there are advantages to having it at the<br />back end of the year.</p></blockquote><p>Noonan also conceded that Ireland will revise its official growth targets down soon. That would bring them back into line with analyst forecasts, which suggest GDP will expand by just 0.7% in 2012 (not the 1.3% currently inked in).</p><!-- Block 22 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">2.35pm:</span> EU taskforce chief <strong>Horst Reichenbach</strong> appeared to be in cheerful - if measured - mood at the press conference where its quarterly report was formally unveiled this lunchtime (see <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating#block-18\">12.45pm</a>) <strong>Helena Smith</strong> tells me.</p><p>We'll have a full report from Reichenbach shortly, but first <strong>Helena</strong> has an update on the press conference just given by Evangelos Venizelos, the Greek finance minister (as mentioned at <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating#block-19\">1.03pm</a>).  <br /> <br />She writes:</p><blockquote><p>In the wake of Evangelos Venizelos' maiden appearance as leader-elect of the socialist Pasok party, Greek media are insisting that he wants to be called - and should now be referred to - as \"Vangelis\", a more common touch that will go down \"well with the people.\" Obviously, the French-trained law professor, a big fan of Winston Churchill, has also learned a lesson or two from our very own David \"Dave\" Cameron.</p></blockquote><p><br />  <br />Our colleague Rob McSweeney points out that \"Vangelis\" is also <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vangelis\">the Greek composer</a> who wrote the music for <strong><em>Chariots of Fire</em></strong> and <strong><em>Blade Runner</em></strong>. Perhaps Venizelos is hoping that some of the glamour will rub off....</p><p>Anyway, <strong>Helena</strong> continues that:</p><blockquote><p>Venizelos reiterated that he will step down from his post at the finance ministry on Monday. But it has yet to be decided who will replace him. With the national Unity government expected to be in power for a matter of weeks it was thought that Lucas Papademos, the technocrat prime minister and former vice president of the European Central Bank would assume the position. <br /> <br />A senior Papademos aide said: \"That is one possibility but it has still not been decided. At this point we just don't know.\" <br /> <br />The coalition government has a raft of reforms - at least nine at the last count -- that it has to pass before parliament can be dissolved.   The second adjustment program, also known Greecec's second bailout or rescue package, similarly has to be ratified by the 300-seat House.</p></blockquote><!-- Block 21 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408756'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2012/3/15/1331810244464/Ukraine-flag-001.jpg' alt='Ukraine flag' width='60' height='40' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">2.01pm:</span> More developments in Ukraine. Standard &amp; Poor's has just lowered its credit rating outlook to negative, from stable - just a couple of hours after the country admitted that it wants to renegotiate its IMF loan, and not pay it back for <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating#block-15\">another decade</a>.</p><!-- Block 20 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408757'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2012/3/15/1331817440914/Bank-of-England-policymak-004.jpg' alt='Bank of England policymaker Ben Broadbent' width='220' height='132' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Ben Broadbent today. Photograph: Eddie Keogh/Reuters</figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">1.43pm:</span> One of the Bank of England's policymakers warned today that the eurozone crisis is at the heart of Britain's current economic woes.</p><p><strong>Ben Broadbent</strong>, one of the nine people who set monetary policy, told City executives that the UK had been particularly winded by the problems in the eurozone, because its banks have such large overseas balance sheets</p><p>Speaking hours after Fitch cut its outlook on the UK to negative, Broadbent argued that bank balance sheets are a more significant issue than household debt:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>It remains the case that the most important risks facing the UK banks, and therefore the supply of domestic credit, emanate from outside the UK.</p></blockquote><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-uk-economic-woes-broadbent\">More details here</a>.</p><!-- Block 19 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">1.03pm:</span> <strong>Evangelos Venizelos</strong>, Greece's finance minister (until Monday) has just pledged that the country should return to growth next year.</p><p>Speaking in Athens, Venizelos said that 2012 would be a very tough year for Greeks, but offered the hope that economic growth will return in 2013. In an apparent nod to the EU taskforce's new report (see <strong><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating#block-18\">12.45pm</a></strong>), he said that structural reforms should be \"our primary goal to make Greece competitive again\".</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408758'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2012/3/15/1331817694146/Greek-Finance-Minister-Ev-007.jpg' alt='Greek Finance Minister Evangelos Venizelos' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Photograph: Olivier Hoslet/EPA</figcaption></figure><p>Last night, Venizelos announced that he will quit the Greek Treasury once he becomes the leader of the socialist Pasok party this weekend. His mind is turning to the upcoming general election, saying that the bailout programme \"does not mark the end of politics in Greece\". <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating#block-12\">This morning's polling data</a>, of course, showed that the election will probably deliver a very divided parliament where politicking will be relentless.</p><p>Venizelos also acknowledged that he has experienced a remarkable eight months as finance minister, saying:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Some day I will write my memoirs on what I've witnessed in the last eight months.</p></blockquote><!-- Block 18 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408759'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/5/12/1305203064788/Live-blog-news-flash-001.jpg' alt='Live blog: news flash newsflash' width='40' height='40' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">12.45pm:</span> The EU taskforce to Greece has declared that \"a lot has been achieved\" over the past three months, as it released its second quartely report.</p><p>But at first glance, the report also shows there is also an awful lot more to do.</p><p>Today's report identifies two key areas of progress. Funds provided by the EU to stimulate growth are, apparently, being \"better targeted and spent\". </p><p>Second, technical assistance is now being provided to Greece in nine key areas with the support of around 20 member states, the commission and the IMF.</p><p><strong>Jose Manuel Barroso</strong>, EC president, declared:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The support provided by the commission's taskforce is a key instrument to support growth and jobs in Greece. The solidarity shown by many member states, the commission, and other international institutions is a very encouraging signal for this country. Let's build a future for Greece together.</p></blockquote><p>But what has actually been achieved? The taskforce cites four examples:</p><p>• €946m was collected in tax arrears compared to initial target of €400m.<br />• The backlog of tax cases pending in court has been reduced by 15% in four months, and should be reduced by 80% by the end of 2012<br />• France and Germany are supporting a major administration reform of central and local government, including \"assessment of civil servants' competences\" and a shake-up of ICT and human resources structures in ministries<br />• Liberalisation of access to and exercise of regulated professions</p><p>The full report is available <a href=\"http://ec.europa.eu/commission_2010-2014/president/news/speeches-statements/pdf/qr_march2012_en.pdf\">here</a> (as a pdf).</p><!-- Block 17 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408760'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2010/5/6/1273135348318/Live-blog---Ireland-flag-001.jpg' alt='Live blog - Ireland flag' width='60' height='40' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">12.22pm:</span> The chief of Ireland's central bank is under fire today after he called for taxpayer rescued Irish banks to be able to start repossessing homes.</p><p>From Dublin, <strong>Henry McDonald</strong> explains that the row also provides an insight into how an overheated property market during the Irish boom proved to be so disastrous not only for the republic but contributed to the fiscal firestorm throughout the eurozone:</p><blockquote><p>Patrick Honohan said that banks such as Allied Irish and Bank of Ireland should be more agressive in seizing houses and property where owners fail to meet repayments. In a speech in Limerick Honohan said it was \"surely past time\" that the banks were more pro-active in dealing with debt-burdened buy to let property investors who borrowed during the Celtic tiger boom.  </p><p>His remarks have sparked anger in Dublin with New Beginning, a legal group working on behalf of distressed mortgage owners, suggesting today that the head of the Irish central bank needs \"a reality check\".  David Hall of New Beginning said it was the banks' fault given that they agressively encouraged average income buyers to borrow for buy-for-let properties during the years of rapid economic growth. </p></blockquote><p>Henry also provides some figures that bear out how much was invested in buy-for-let properties when the Celtic tiger was roaring:</p><p><strong>• Approximately 250,000 mortgages are out there in the Irish market that were bought originally as buy-to-lets.<br />• The value of all buy-to-let mortgages could more than €30bn.<br />• An average house bought at the peak of the Irish property boom was around €311,000 but it is now estimated according to Godbody Stockbrokers to be just under €100,000.</strong></p><p>Meanwhile the most recent projection from the state's Central Statistical Office estimates that Irish housing prices have fallen by an average of 48% since the boom although some forecasters say the drop is even steeper.</p><!-- Block 16 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">12.10pm:</span> There have been protests in Athens today against Greece's record unemployment rate (which <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating#block-10\">hit 20.3% in the last three months of 2011, as reported at 10.09am</a>).</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408761'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2012/3/15/1331813602371/Shipyard-workers-shout-sl-007.jpg' alt='Shipyard workers shout slogans during a protest against high unemployment in their sector in Athens' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Photograph: John Kolesidis/Reuters</figcaption></figure><p>Here's a picture of shipyard workers shouting slogans outside the finance ministry this morning.</p><p>Like much of Greece's industry, shipbuilding has been hit hard by the downturn. <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2011/aug/04/greek-shipyards-luxury-yachts\">We reported last summer</a> that shipyards that once churned out cargo ships and ferries were now mainly producing yachts for the wealthiest.</p><p><strong>UPDATE:</strong> Reader <a href=\"https://twitter.com/#!/Finisterre67\">Finisterre67</a> flags up that Greece's employment minister has unveiled a project for social rehabilitation. The National Emergency Social Network for Social Intervention is meant to offer support for the poor and 'weakest' in Greece, including the unemployed.</p><p>You can <a href=\"http://t.co/5teT2TIM\">read more here</a> (if you can read Greek).</p><!-- Block 15 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408762'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2012/3/15/1331810244464/Ukraine-flag-001.jpg' alt='Ukraine flag' width='60' height='40' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">11.55am:</span> Beyond the eurozone, Ukraine has admitted this morning that it is in talks with the International Monetary Fund in an attempt to restructure its debts.</p><p><strong>Ukraine revealed that it wants to delay repayment of $3bn which falls due this year for another decade.</strong></p><p>First deputy economy minister <strong>Vadim Kopylov</strong> told reporters in Kiev that:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Talks are being held now on restructuring the debt falling due this year ... $3bn </p><p>We need to discuss delaying repayment of these funds by 10 years.</p></blockquote><p>This debt is part of a loan given to Ukraine by the IMF at the start of the current financial crisis. Relations between the two sides have deteriorated recently, with <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/feedarticle/10139783\">the IMF urging the Kiev government, so far unsuccessfully, to raise gas prices</a>.</p><!-- Block 14 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408763'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/GUARDIAN/Pix/pictures/2012/3/12/1331565434046/Mario-Monti-italy-prime-m-004.jpg' alt='Mario Monti italy prime minister' width='220' height='132' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Photograph: Saul Loeb/AFP/Getty Images</figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">11.22am:</span> Mario Monti is getting to grips with Italy's manufacturing industry.</p><p>He's due to hold crunch talks with unions and bosses over his labour reform plans next Tuesday, and will also hold meet with the bosses of Fiat tomorrow, amid fears that it could close a car factory. Falling sales in Italy (as we touched on at <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/15/eurozone-crisis-greece-uk-fitch-rating#block-7\">9.35am</a>) have led to fears that Fiat might ditch plans to spend €1.5bn refurbishing its plants.</p><p>As Reuters points out, Monti's first official meeting with CEO Sergio Marchionne and chairman John Elkann should be a pleasant affair:</p><blockquote><p>The prime minister is well acquainted with Fiat, since he served on its board from 1988 to 1993 and is a friend of the Agnelli family, Fiat's controlling shareholder. He attended John Elkann's wedding in 2004.</p></blockquote><p>Italian debt has strengthened in value again today, indicating that Monti does have a clear window of opportunity to implement reforms. But economists warn that it typically takes a decade for structural changes to deliver benefits.</p><!-- Block 13 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408764'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2012/3/15/1331811064927/EU-and-eurozone-employmen-001.jpg' alt='EU and eurozone employment data.' width='220' height='480' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">10.55am:</span> This morning's eurozone labour force data shows a rise in unemployment, and a drop in real earnings for those in work.</p><p>Eurostat reported that employment across the region fell by 0.2% quarter-on-quarter, and also 0.2% year-on-year, in the last three months of 2011.</p><p>Southern Europe suffered the most:</p><p><strong>Italy:</strong> -0.1% quarter-on-quarter, and -0.2% year-on-year<br /><strong>Spain:</strong> -1.0% quarter-on-quarter and -3.0% year-on-year<br /><strong>Portugal:</strong> -2.7% quarter-on-quarter, and -3.1% year-on-year</p><p>The data also showed that annual wages grew by 2.5% in Q4 2011, below the headline inflation rate.</p><!-- Block 12 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">10.42am:</span> News in from Athens where Helena Smith our correspondent says a new poll has proved that Greeks will vote \"with their pockets\" in upcoming general elections.</p><blockquote><p>The survey published in the satirical weekly To Pontiki (the mouse) revealed that <strong>58%</strong> of those asked would take the economy into account – and particularly their own economic survival – before casting votes in elections scheduled for late April or early May. Another <strong>47%</strong> said they would prioritise punishing politicians who were responsible for getting Greece into the financial mess that has brought it to the brink of economic collapse.</p></blockquote><p><br />The survey, by the Greek polling company Pulse RC, showed that support for the two main parties had also dropped precipitously in what is likely to be interpreted as a potentially dangerous development for a country that is in dire need of political stability.</p><blockquote><p>The centre right <strong>New Democracy</strong> was still tipped to emerge as the election's winner but with just 23% would not gain a working majority in Athens' 300-seat parliament.<br />The socialist <strong>Pasok</strong>, voted into power with a landslide victory in October 2009, would pick up a mere 13.5% according to the survey – proof of the pummelling it has taken for pursuing painful austerity policies in return for international aid.<br />By contrast, backing for smaller political groups that have taken a strong anti-bailout stance remained high with the hardline <strong>KKE</strong> communist party and radical <strong>Left Coalition</strong> taking 12.5% each. The <strong>Democratic Left</strong>, led by the popular Fotis Kouvelis, would win 10.5% and the neo-fascist <strong>Chrysi Avg</strong>i (Golden Dawn) 3.5%. A breakaway group formed by dissident Pasok MPs and unveiled to the public yesterday – the party, known as <strong>Social Contract</strong>, headed by the former national economy minister Louka Katseli – was not included in the poll.<br />The survey was conducted on March 12-13 after Athens pulled off the biggest debt restructuring in history, swapping privately held bonds for new papers with less than half the nominal value.<br />Some 31% of Greeks told pollsters they considered the bond swap \"negative\" for Greece – compared with 26% who considered it \"positive,\" while 36% said they did not believe it would change the country's plight.</p></blockquote><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408765'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2012/3/15/1331808959516/Independent-MP-and-former-007.jpg' alt='Independent MP and former PASOK minister Louka Katseli announces a new political party.' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Louka Katseli announces the creation of her Social Contract party this week. Photograph: Pantelis Saitas/EPA</figcaption></figure><p>The findings will be food for thought for European policy makers not least in Germany, the main provider of rescue funds for Greece to date, who have openly opposed elections being held at such a sensitive time. Many fear that Athens will not adopt the necessary reforms to rein in its massive debt and make its economy competitive if it lacks a strong government. Wolfgang Schauble, the German finance minister, has said he would prefer Greece to take a leaf out of Italy's book and remain under the stewardship of its technocrat prime minister, Lucas Papademos.  </p><p>But senior officials cautioned against taking the poll results too seriously.</p><p>One insider told <strong>Helena</strong>:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p><br />At this point in time polls should not be trusted</p><p>The options aren't clear. Pasok is in a transition awaiting a new leader [ahead of elections for a new party head this Sunday] and those who are \"undecided\" number more than 20%.  Often polls show smaller parties winning enough votes to get in [parliament] before elections but then they are proved to be wrong.</p></blockquote><!-- Block 11 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">10.24am:</span> Some good news for Ireland, as it struggles through the eurocrisis. <strong>Oil has been struck off the south coast of the country.</strong></p><p><strong>Henry McDonald</strong>, our correspondent in Dublin, reports that Ireland's commercial viable oil well has successfully started production today.</p><blockquote><p>Providence Resources whose headquarters are in Dublin revealed this morning that the well 50 kilometres off the south Cork coast is producing 3,500 barrels per day.  The company said the outflow was far ahead of its target of 1,800 barrels at the well in the Barryroe oil field.</p><p>Providence also says the well has shown a rate of 2.93m standard cubic feet per day, which could eventually yield around 4,000 standard barrels per day.</p><p>At present price levels, this would be equivalent to a market price at around $500,000. A recent audit suggested that the reservoir could have a total capacity of almost 1bn barrels – which are currently selling for around $125 per barrel.</p></blockquote><p>Providence says that mineral analysis has confirmed that the oil is light sweet, and is 'highly mobile', which should allow for relatively straightforward extraction. It also wants to drill another five offshore wells.</p><p>The company is run by Tony O'Reilly junior, son of the former rugby player and media magnate. He claimed this morning that the find could be a \"big boom\" to the Irish exchequer. <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/marketforceslive/2012/mar/15/oil-find-boosts-ireland\">My colleague Nick Fletcher reports</a> that shares in the company jumped more than 10% this morning.</p><!-- Block 10 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408766'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2010/5/5/1273067757521/Live-blog---Greece-flag-001.jpg' alt='Live blog - Greece flag' width='60' height='40' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">10.09am:</span> The latest employment data from Greece underlines the depth of the country's economic crisis.</p><p><strong>The unemployment rate hit 20.3% in the fourth quarter of 2011, from the third quarter. That's the highest rate since records began.</strong></p><p>We already knew that the Greek unemployment rate had hit 21% in December, but today's stats are based on a larger sample size.</p><!-- Block 9 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">9.55am:</span> News from the bond markets, where Spain has sold €3bn of bonds, with demand strong.</p><p>Bid-to-cover ratios (the measure of demand) rose, and yields fell – showing that investors would accept a lower rate of return for holding Spanish debt.</p><p><strong>2015 bond:</strong> €1,004bn sold, average yield 2.44%, vs 2.966% last time, bid-to-cover 5.0 vs 4.4<br /><strong>2016 bond:</strong> €976m sold, average yield 3.374% vs 3.748%, bit-to-cover 4.1 vs 2.2<br /><strong>2018 bond:</strong> €1.029bn sold: average yield 4.193%, bid-to-cover ratio 2.9%</p><p>Usual proviso about banks being well-stocked with liquidity by the European Central Bank applies.</p><!-- Block 8 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">9.46am:</span> Bloomberg has crunched the numbers, and <a href=\"http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-03-15/greek-bonds-signal-2-6-billion-payout-on-credit-default-swaps.html\">reckons that the insurance on Greece's restructured bonds will pay out $2.6bn (€2bn)</a>.</p><p>That's less than the previous forecasts of €3.2bn, which will be some relief for the banks on the wrong end of these credit default swap contracts. That list includes KA Finanz AG, which holds the 'bad' assets spun out of Kommunalkredit Austria AG.</p><p>The details of the CDSs will be sorted out on 19 March, when a particular Greek bond is auctioned off to find its true value.</p><!-- Block 7 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">9.35am:</span> We've already had one piece of poor economic data from the eurozone. Car registrations (a measure of new sales) across the region fell by 11.8% in February, compared to the previous year.</p><p>The fall was blamed on weak demand from Italy and France.</p><p>Better news from the UK motor industry though – <a href=\"http://www.smmt.co.uk/2012/03/smmt-uk-automotive-manufacturing-february-2012/\">car production rose by 23.5% in February</a>.</p><!-- Block 6 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">9.06am:</span> Here's today's agenda:</p><p>• <strong>Italian general dovernment debt data</strong>: 9.30am GMT / 10.30am CET <br />• <strong>Eurozone employment data for Q4 2011</strong>: 10am GMT / 11a, CET<br />• <strong>Bank of England's Ben Broadbent speech in London</strong>: 11.30am GMT<br />• <strong>EU Task Force to Greece holds press conference:</strong> noon GMT / 2pm EET<br />• <strong>Evangelos Venizelos holds press conference:</strong> noon GMT / 2pm EET<br />• <strong>Weekly US jobless data</strong> - 12.30pm GMT / 8.30am EST<br />• <strong>IMF meeting in Washington</strong></p><!-- Block 5 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408767'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2012/3/15/1331802763682/Flag-of-Switzerland-001.jpg' alt='Flag of Switzerland' width='60' height='40' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">9.00am:</span> In Switzerland, the central bank has vowed to maintain its cap against the euro \"with the utmost determination\".</p><p>In the last few minutes the Swiss National Bank announced that it voted unanimously to maintain the swiss franc at a rate of 1.20 to the euro. That cap was brought in last September, after a rush of capital threatened to push the Swiss franc to parity with the euro.</p><p>In a statement, the SNB vowed to buy foreign exchange reserves in \"unlimited quantities\" (ie, buying the euro and selling the 'Swissie' to maintain the current exchange rate).</p><p>This comes after the Swiss government bucked recent trends and actually raised its forecast for GDP growth in 2012, to 0.8% from 0.5%. It trimmed its prediction for 2013, though, to 1.8% from 1.9%.</p><!-- Block 4 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387408768'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/2/24/1330103561904/Danny-Alexander-007.jpg' alt='Danny Alexander' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Danny Alexander. Photograph: David Levene</figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">8.47am:</span> And here's the political reaction to Fitch's announcement:</p><p>First <strong>Danny Alexander</strong>, chief secretary to the Treasury:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>This is a salutary reminder as to why Britain needs to deal with the enormous debts and deficit that we inherited, why we have got to stick to those plans</p><p>And it should be a wake-up call to anyone who thinks we can afford as a country to loosen the purse strings. We can't afford to do that, and that is why there will be no unfunded giveaways in next week's budget.</p></blockquote><p>And here's how Ed Balls, shadow chancellor, responded:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>I think the credit rating agencies are a weather vane – they tell you the direction in which things are moving. And the UK going on to a negative watch shows that there's a growing worry that our economy's not growing, that unemployment's rising, that our borrowing is not coming down as George Osborne had planned. Now I've said to George Osborne always, don't set your policies by the credit rating agencies, but they are a weather vane and they say the wind is blowing in a difficult direction for the British economy. </p></blockquote><!-- Block 3 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">8.32am:</span> City analysts are in general agreement that Fitch's warning has sunk any lingering possibility that George Osborne might announce any giveaways in next week's budget. Here's a roundup of some early comments:</p><h2>Investec</h2><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p><br />While satisfied with the government's fiscal efforts, the outlook change is put down to still high deficit and increasing indebtedness leaving the UK vulnerable to further adverse economic shocks. The negative outlook represents a slightly higher than 50% change of a rating downgrade over the next two years according to Fitch and the rating agency does not expect to resolve the negative outlook until 2014.</p></blockquote><h2>Michael Hewson, senior market analyst at CMC Markets:</h2><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Any thoughts in some parts that the chancellor might be tempted to embark on a bit of a budget giveaway next week as a result of coming in under his borrowing forecasts for 2011 are very likely to be put to one side after last night's warning. The agency warned that the UK has very limited space to absorb further adverse economic shocks. </p></blockquote><h2>Howard Archer of IHS Global Insight:</h2><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p><br />The move by Fitch could not come at a more telling time for Chancellor George Osborne as he enters into the final planning stages for next Wednesday's budget. Fitch's move heaps further pressure on the chancellor to stick to his fiscal austerity plans and to resist any temptation for unfunded giveaways.</p></blockquote><h2>Gary Jenkins of Swordfish Research</h2><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>I still don't think that any of the agencies would dare downgrade the UK in the Queen's diamond jubilee year … that would just be rude.</p></blockquote><!-- Block 2 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">8.19am:</span> If you missed Fitch's announcement that it had put the UK credit rating on negative outlook last night, here's how <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/14/fitch-uk-aaa-rating-at-risk\">my colleague Heather Stewart reported it</a>:</p><blockquote><p>George Osborne faced fresh questions about the credibility of his austerity policies just days before the budget on Wednesday night, when Fitch became the second of the major credit ratings agencies to warn that the UK's coveted AAA-rating is at risk.</p><p>Echoing the recent decision by Moody's to place the UK on so-called \"negative watch\", which signals that it could be stripped of AAA status, Fitch said a weaker than expected recovery in the economy could jeopardise Osborne's chances of tackling the debt burden.</p></blockquote><p>Fitch identified the eurozone debt crisis as a key threat to the government's tax and spending forecasts, along with the danger that the 'supply capacity' of the economy has suffered permanent damage (which would mean Britain would struggle to post solid growth).</p><p>It's important to note that Fitch isn't urging Osborne to change his fiscal plans. Indeed, Treasury officials were quick to point out that Fitch warned that any \"discretionary fiscal easing\" (ie, ditching the current deficit-reduction plans) would also probably lead to the AAA being cut.</p><!-- Block 1 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">8.15am:</span> Good morning, and welcome to <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/14/eurozone-crisis-markets-rally-greece\">our rolling coverage of the European debt crisis</a>.</p><p>Today, the taskforce sent to Greece by the EU will be giving its quarterly update. Horst Reichenbach will tell an Athens press conference whether he is happy with the progress made by the Greek government in the last three months.</p><p>Greece will also be on the International Monetary Fund's agenda – it is meeting to discuss the aid programme for the country and vote on whether to provide €28bn in new funding (its share of the second financial support programme).</p><p>Meanwhile, we are digesting <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/14/fitch-uk-aaa-rating-at-risk\">Fitch's warning last night</a> that it could cut the UK's credit rating within the next two years. It put Britain's AAA rating on \"negative watch\" – just a week before the Budget.</p>","headline":"Eurozone crisis live: IMF approves €28bn loan for Greece as S&amp;P sets CCC rating","trailText":"<p>The head of the EU taskforce for Greece has delivered his quarterly report, as the UK digests Fitch's warning that its AAA-credit rating could be cut</p>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2012/2/10/1328873356461/Greece-EU-003.jpg"