,"photographer":"Olivia Harris","altText":"Traders in the City of London.","height":"276","credit":"Olivia Harris/Reuters","caption":"A trading floor in the city of London. Photograph: Olivia Harris/Reuters","width":"460"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"Eurozone crisis live: Markets tumble amid fears over Spain and Greece","webPublicationDate":"2012-07-23T06:55:00Z","sectionName":"Business","sectionId":"business","id":"business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1","fields":{"secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2010/11/30/1291113270072/Eurozone-in-crisis-003.jpg","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/397yy","displayHint":"news","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-4a586db1-0349-4c0f-9366-a9a4a122985f\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/7/13/1342159502267/a1f9a41e-a8d8-4344-8acd-170310379d8f-620.jpeg\" alt=\"A structure showing the Euro currency sign is seen in front of the European Central Bank (ECB) headquarters in Frankfurt July 11, 2012.\" width=\"620\" height=\"372\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>A bad start to the week has seen Spanish bond yields leap and the euro slide below the $1.21 mark against the US dollar. (Alex Domanski/Reuters)</figcaption> </figure>","standfirst":"• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1#block-500d777d95cbd01cfadc5b1e\">Italian and Spanish stocks fall 5% before recovering</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1#block-500d47efb579b8fa1c624336\">Italy and Spain ban short-selling; City unimpressed</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1#block-500cf4ec95cbd01cfadc5afb\">• Spanish 10-year bond yield climbs over 7.51%</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1#block-500d1994b579b8fa1c624326\">Germany fuels new fears of Greek euro exit</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1#block-500d68b8b579b8fa1c624345\">Putin says Russia won't reduce amount of euros in its reserves</a>","hasStoryPackage":"true","lastModified":"2012-10-24T17:19:12.023+01:00","firstPublicationDate":"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00","body":"<div id=\"block-500d7e0fb579b8fa1c62434b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>And with that, it's time to shut up shop for what initially appeared as if it would be a quiet day, but ended up being anything but. Thanks for all the comments, and we'll be back tomorrow.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d777d95cbd01cfadc5b1e\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">European markets end sharply lower</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>So after a particularly grim day, European markets have closed and its time to rake over the pieces.</p> <p>Growing fears that Spain could need a bailout, worries about whether Greece will get more money or will instead quit the eurozone, and a drop in EU confidence have conspired to sent shares and the euro sharply lower and bond yields higher.</p> <p>News of a ban on short selling in Italy and Spain - whether misguided or not - seemed to help haul markets slightly back from the brink.</p> <p>The <strong>FTSE 100</strong> finished 117.90 at 5533.87 with not a single riser, while <strong>Germany's Dax</strong> dropped 3.18% and <strong>France's Cac</strong> closed 2.89% lower.</p> <p><strong>Italy's FTSE MIB</strong> was down 2.76% and <strong>Spain's Ibex</strong> lost 1.1%, but it is worth bearing in mind that both these markets had earlier plunged around 5%.</p> <p>Greece, with the IMF making a half hearted denial of reports it was not prepared to provide more funding, is down 9.8%.</p> <p>As for bonds, the Spanish 10 year yield is currently at 7.48% while Italy's is at 6.33%. A Spanish bond auction tomorrow could prove interesting.</p> <p>The euro hit $1.2067 against the dollar, its lowest for two years, before recovering to the current $1.2119.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Chris Beauchamp, market analyst at IG Index, said:<br /> <br /> Eurozone leaders hoping for a quiet few weeks will be sorely disappointed. Short-selling bans on banking and insurance stocks by financial authorities in Rome and Madrid are a sure sign that all is not well, although I fear that these restrictions will only offer the most temporary of respites. After the summit in June that provided a brief burst of euphoria, there were mutterings that the crisis was not over, and the pessimists have now been proved right.</p> <p><br /> We may rapidly be approaching a decisive moment for the eurozone; previous bailouts were of smaller countries that were of manageable size. Spain is a different order of magnitude entirely, and it may not be possible to rescue this economy in the same way that Greece, Ireland and Portugal were bailed out. Eurozone leaders will likely hold yet another summit, but they will need more than fine words if they are to truly save the single currency.</p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d68b8b579b8fa1c624345\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>The Italian prime minister, Mario Monti, has been dampening speculation there might be an emergency European summit following the events of recent days.</strong></p> <p>Speaking after a meeting with the Russian president, Vladimir Putin, Monti said it was not yet time for such a summit, and anyway, the decision to call one was in the hands of the EU council president, Herman Van Rompuy.</p> <p>Monti also said it would be helpful if the European Central Bank pumped fresh funds into the eurozone economy but again, there was no immediate need for such a move. (The ECB's bond buying programme seems to have dried up, by the way. Last week there were no purchases under the securities markets programme, keeping the total bond buys at &euro;211.5bn.)</p> <p>So no panic, nothing to see here. Somehow don't think the markets are going to be terribly reassured by all that, if that was the aim. Even if past summits have tended to produce only a temporary burst of optimism, before markets decided there was nothing concrete agreed after all.</p> <p>Meanwhile both Monti and Putin said after their meeting that <strong>Russia has no intention of reducing the share of euros in its reserves,</strong> despite the current pressure on the single currency. According to Reuters, Putin said:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Russia is not decreasing the (share) of euro-denominated assets in its reserves and has no plans to change it.</p> </blockquote> <p>The Russian central bank has around 40% of its foreign exchange reserves in euro-denominated assets, mainly government bonds.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-6029f1ab-c36e-4d84-8f90-3265745a0ee0\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/7/23/1343056254097/7c02bb93-83ba-44b9-9754-b30dd818448e-460.jpeg\" alt=\"Russian president Vladimir Putin (right) and Italian prime minister Mario Monti (left) meet in Sochi, Russia. Photo: Epa/Alexey Druzhinyn/Ria Novosti \" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Russian president Vladimir Putin (right) and Italian prime minister Mario Monti (left) meet in Sochi, Russia. Photo: Epa/Alexey Druzhinyn/Ria Novosti </figcaption> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d5ea0b579b8fa1c624340\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Spain's action to cut its budget deficit may not be enough to stave off a bailout, but even that is not going ahead without protests in the streets. After <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1#block-500d151695cbd01cfadc5b01\">the weekend's march</a> from the regions to Madrid, here's a demonstration from today.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-d029a21f-ee2d-4393-a0fb-01756ef0e1c2\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/7/23/1343053286361/24a30367-24d5-4856-85f6-7496f1bf638e-460.jpeg\" alt=\"Civil servants hold up placards as they protest against government austerity measures in Madrid. Reuters/Andrea Comas \" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Civil servants hold up placards as they protest against government austerity measures in Madrid. Reuters/Andrea Comas </figcaption> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d5c72b579b8fa1c62433f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Some commentary on the eurozone consumer confidence figures from Annalisa Piazza at Newedge Strategy:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The outcome is weaker than anticipated and it marks the weakest reading since August 2009, when the euro area was in a deep recessionary mode.</p> <p>Although the pace of decline in activity is currently less profound than three years ago, households feel the pressure of a record high unemployment rate, tight fiscal conditions and the exceptional uncertainties of financial markets.</p> <p>Falling equities have added further uncertainties to the already compromised picture for households in the past few weeks and the effects of the ECB policy accommodation are certainly far from supporting confidence amongst consumers. <br /> <br /> </p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d59a295cbd01cfadc5b17\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Surprise, surprise, confidence in the eurozone has slumped again.</p> <p><strong>According to the European commission, the consumer confidence index fell to -21.6 in July, compared to expectations of -20 and a figure of -19.8 in June.</strong></p> <p>This is the lowest since August 2009. With markets plunging, austerity gripping much of the region, the prospect of a bailout for Spain and Greece exiting the euro, the index is hardly likely to show much improvement in the near future either.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d57cf95cbd01cfadc5b15\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>The International Monetary Fund has played down <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1#block-500d1994b579b8fa1c624326\">earlier reports that it was about to pull the plug on Greece and would not give the country any more funds.</a></p> <p>It says it will meet with Greek authorities tomorrow - the day the mission by the Troika of IMF, ECB and EC is due to arrive in the country to check the progress of its economic reforms. An IMF spokesperson said:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The IMF is supporting Greece in overcoming its economic difficulties. An IMF mission will start discussion with the country's authorities on 24 July on how to bring Greece's economic program, which is supported by IMF financial assistance, back on track.</p> </blockquote> <p>\"Back on track\" of course is an admission the Greeks have not met their end of the bargain, but whether it means the country will be given more time and enough money is a moot point. As we reported earlier, some members of the German government are not convinced Greece will meet its targets, and are openly talking of a possible Grexit - a Greek exit from the euro.</p> <p><br /><br /></p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d5575b579b8fa1c62433c\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>As forecast, Wall Street has opened sharply lower as the latest worries about the eurozone spread across the Atlantic.</p> <p><strong>The Dow Jones Industrial Average is down around 220 points or 1.7%</strong> in the first 10 minutes or so of trading, and with little in the way of timetabled economic events, it is hard to see much to change the current market sentiment.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d5199b579b8fa1c62433b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Vincent Forest, economist at the Economist Intelligence Unit, points out that the &euro;65bn austerity package announced by the Spanish prime minister, Mariano Rajoy, has clearly failed to convince the markets.</p> <p>Forest warns:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>It is now clear that Spain has entered a self-defeating cycle of austerity and economic contraction.</p> <p>Some intervention either by the European Central Bank or by the European Financial Stability Fund could be required relatively soon, preferably on primary markets. However, given the current divergence of points of views among European countries, such intervention will prove politically difficult.</p> </blockquote>  <p>And with that, I'm handing over to my colleague Nick Fletcher. See you all tomorrow.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d47efb579b8fa1c624336\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>The Law of Unintended Consequences strikes again.</p> <p>The euro has dropped back below $1.21 against the US dollar since <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1#block-500d39f595cbd01cfadc5b0d\">first Italy</a> and <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1#block-500d44b5b579b8fa1c624334\">then Spain</a> outlawed short-selling today, as the financial markets decided the bans were a clear <strong>Sell Signal</strong>.</p> <p>The euro has also dropped to a new three-and-a-half-year low against sterling, meaning <strong>one pound is now worth &euro;1.284</strong>. That's good news for UK holidaymakers, but not for exporters.</p> <p>It's too easy to find City traders and commentators who are critical of the decision to ban short-selling, so here goes:</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/AllisterHeath/status/227385102928330752\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Why is there supposedly something wrong with a market when prices fall, but nothing wrong when they rise? Spain's short selling ban nonsense</p>&mdash; Allister Heath (@AllisterHeath) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/AllisterHeath/status/227385102928330752\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-23T12:50:07+00:00\">July 23, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/WillHedden_IG/status/227384960405893120\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Italian ban - the market rallied a little. Now Spain bans shorting bank stocks and market crashes lower. Panic ensuing.</p>&mdash; Will Hedden (@WillHedden_IG) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/WillHedden_IG/status/227384960405893120\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-23T12:49:33+00:00\">July 23, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/OliverCooper/status/227384621451603968\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>A short-selling ban is the sort of policy Occupy Wall Street would come up with when they were particularly baked. It's just plain stupid.</p>&mdash; Oliver Cooper (@OliverCooper) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/OliverCooper/status/227384621451603968\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-23T12:48:13+00:00\">July 23, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d462395cbd01cfadc5b0f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>The FTSE 100 is hitting new lows for the day, now down 130 points at 5522 (-2.3%).</strong></p> <p>The selloff seemed to gather pace after Italy, and then Spain, announced their short-selling bans.</p> <p>Wall Street is expected to see heavy selling at the open (in around 45 minutes time), with the futures market predicting<strong> a 1.5% drop on the Dow Jones Industrial Average.</strong></p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d44b5b579b8fa1c624334\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>And so it continues &hellip; Spain's market regulator has just announced a ban on the short-selling of All Spanish Securities*, for three months.</p> <p>The move came just an hour after Italy announced a five-day ban on traders selling financial stocks which they didn't already own.</p> <p><em>* - sorry, was some confusion over whether it applies to all Spanish securities, or just banks and insurers. Turns out that it's the former (although \"market-makers\" won't be affected).<br /></em></p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d424d95cbd01cfadc5b0e\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">FITCH: EURO SHOCKS HAVE HURT GLOBAL ECONOMY</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Ratings agency Fitch has warned that negative credit outlooks have risen sharply in the last six months, as the eurozone crisis has harmed the global recovery.</p> <p>In its latest report on the credit market, Fitch said that \"new shocks from the eurozone\" had rippled out across the world on the last six months, continuing to \"drag on the global economic recovery\".</p> <p><strong>Fitch said the number of countries with a \"negative credit outlook\" has almost doubled this year, from 10.3% to 19.8%.</strong></p> <p><strong>More alarmingly, over 48% of 'international public finance' firms are now rated with a negative outlook by Fitch.<br /></strong></p> <p>There has also been a decline in the number of countries and companies with the highest credit ratings, indicating an increase in risk.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/jessbrammar/status/227376230255702017\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Fitch: \"universe of highest grade ratings ('AAA' and 'AA') continues to shrink...sharpest declinein international public finance\"</p>&mdash; Jess Brammar (@jessbrammar) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/jessbrammar/status/227376230255702017\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-23T12:14:52+00:00\">July 23, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d4171b579b8fa1c624330\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Despite today's alarming jump in bond yields, Spain still plans to auction up to &euro;3bn of short-term debt tomorrow. That will indicate how concerned bond traders are about the situation (although three and six-month Spanish debt really ought to sell).</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d3e0bb579b8fa1c62432f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Speaking of Italy, the head of the Union of Italian Provinces (UPI) has warned that some Italian schools may be unable to open after the summer holidays, due to a funding crisis.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/07/23/italy-regions-idUSR1E8I900U20120723\">Via Reuters</a>:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>\"With these cuts we won't be able to guarantee the opening of the school year,\" UPI President Giuseppe Castiglione told reporters in Rome.</p> <p>Piero Lacorazza, president of the province of Potenza in southern Italy, said the comment was \"not an exaggeration\", adding that \"half of the provinces are in serious financial difficulty\".</p> </blockquote> <p>Alarming stuff. Mind you, European government bond market-maker Gus Baratta isn't convinced (and being based in Milan, he should know) &hellip;</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/gusbaratta/status/227374290822123520\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Italian Union of Provinces' head rant on schools not opening because his power center (useless provinces) is being decimated by govt.</p>&mdash; Gustavo Baratta (@gusbaratta) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/gusbaratta/status/227374290822123520\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-23T12:07:10+00:00\">July 23, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d39f595cbd01cfadc5b0d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Just in &ndash; Italy's stock market regulator has banned the short-selling of shares in banks and insurers</strong> (ie, making it illegal to sell a share in a financial stock that you don't actually own).</p> <p>The ban will last until Friday, and appears to have been agreed after regulators saw the FTSE MIB drop by almost 5% this morning (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1#block-500d2b8a95cbd01cfadc5b07\">see 11.46am for details</a>).</p> <p><strong>The news has triggered a small recovery in Milan, with the MIB now down just 2.45% today.</strong></p> <p>Short-selling bans are often introduced once stock markets start tumbling, usually billed as an attempt to weed out unscrupulous speculators &hellip;</p> <p>.&hellip; however, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2012/jul/06/banning-naked-short-selling-eurozone-crisis\">they don't really address the underlying problems</a>. If a bank share is tumbling, usually there's a good reason for it.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d398495cbd01cfadc5b0c\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Luis de Guindos, the Spanish economy minister, has insisted this lunchtime that Spain will not require a bailout.</p> <p>Speaking at a parliamentary hearing into the bailout of the Spanish banking sector, De Guindos argued that Spain's capacity to grow means it will not be forced into a rescue package</p> <p>[hmmm: it's worth remembering that the Bank of Spain has <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1#block-500d090a95cbd01cfadc5afe\">already predicted this morning</a> that the Spanish recession accelerated in the last three months]</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-22809b4d-8919-4912-aba7-116b7f249768\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/7/23/1343043412201/94266736-5a5d-4cd8-b2bf-0319ef318933-460.jpeg\" alt=\"Spain's Economy Minister Luis de Guindos pours himself coffee at the start of a parliamentary hearing at the Spanish parliament in Madrid July 23, 2012. \" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Hot water? No, coffee. Luis de Guindos pours himself a cup at the start of today's parliamentary hearing. (Susana Vera/ Reuters).</figcaption> </figure>  <p>De Guindos also warned that there is \"bailout fatigue\" among the EU, more than two years after Greece's first rescue loan was agreed.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d2b8a95cbd01cfadc5b07\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">MARKETS CONTINUE TO FALL</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>European stock markets have suffered a heavy, wide-ranging selloff this morning, driven by speculation over a possible full-blown Spanish bailout (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1#block-500cf9f0b579b8fa1c62431d\">see 8.14am</a> and <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1#block-500d1ec0b579b8fa1c624327\">10.52am</a>) and a Greek exit from the euro (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1#block-500d1994b579b8fa1c624326\">see 10.29</a>).</p> <p>Concerns over eurozone debt are now raging, after a few weeks out of the spotlight. City traders fear that the crisis is entering a new phase, with renewed fears that the eurozone could splinter.</p> <p>The Spanish and Italian stock markets have suffered the deepest losses (<em>and were down 5% a little while ago</em>), reflecting fears over both country's credit-worthiness. Spain's 10-year bond yields remain <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1#block-500d020cb579b8fa1c62431f\">above the 7.5% mark</a>, a euro-era record).</p> <p>Here's a late-morning roundup:</p> <p><strong>Spain's IBEX 35:</strong> - 251 points at 5995, - 4.02%<br /><strong>Italy's FTSE MIB:</strong> -603 points at 12462, - 4.62%<br /><strong>FTSE 100:</strong> - 97 points at 5554, - 1.7%<br /><strong>German DAX</strong>: -115 points at 6514, - 1.7%<br /><strong>French CAC:</strong> -66 points at 3127, -2.09%</p> <p><strong>David Jones</strong>, chief market strategist at IG Index, said that fears over Spain's financial health are driving markets down:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The familiar worries started on Friday with Spanish region Valencia requiring assistance from the government &ndash; and speculation over the weekend is suggesting there could be a further six regions that require help.</p> <p>In addition there are also murmurings that due to its inability to meet the terms of its bailout, Greece will receive no further IMF aid [<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1#block-500d1994b579b8fa1c624326\">see 10.29</a>].</p> </blockquote> <p>Jones also points out that, back in August 2011, the FTSE 100 shed 1000 points in just two weeks, adding:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>There is nothing to suggest that today's slide heralds a drop of this magnitude, but traditional low summer volumes could well accentuate market nerves in the days ahead.</p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d240db579b8fa1c624329\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Clunk</strong>. The yield on Germany's 10-year bonds just hit yet another record low, of just <strong>1.126%</strong>. </p> <p><strong>UPDATE:</strong> That came after Germany sold &euro;2.7bn of 12-month bonds at a new record low cost. Investors agreed to a yield of -0.054% (down from 0.019% last time) which means they are guaranteed to get back less than they paid when the debt matures in July 2013.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d23bfb579b8fa1c624328\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Interesting developments in Germany.</p> <p>1) A government spokesman has said they have not received any signal from the IMF that it is refusing to provide more support for Greece (as discussed at 10.29).</p> <p>2) German finance minister <strong>Wolfgang Sch&auml;uble</strong> is planning to meet with Spain's <strong>Luis de Guindos</strong> tomorrow. </p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d1ec0b579b8fa1c624327\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Megan Greene</strong>, eurocrisis expert at <strong>Roubini Global Economics</strong>, has predicted that European leaders could be forced to call another emergency summit soon, unless Spain's bond yields drop back.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/economistmeg/status/227335049165565953\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Anyone else looking at Spanish bond yields today and having a flashback to last July with Italy? When's the emergency EU summit...?</p>&mdash; Megan Greene (@economistmeg) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/economistmeg/status/227335049165565953\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-23T09:31:14+00:00\">July 23, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure>  <p>Last July's emergency summit was the event where Greece's second bailout was agreed (in principle). That helped to calm the markets for a few weeks, before they tumbled in August as it became clear that the plan lacked teeth.</p> <p>in the present climate, though, leaders would need to come up with something pretty solid to reassure the City.</p> <p>A full-scale Spanish aid package would, of course, dwarf anything previously put together since the crisis began. Taking Spain out the financial markets for the next two-and-a-half years could cost at least &euro;300bn.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/Pawelmorski/status/227327150544535552\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Back-of-an-envelope extra Spanish bailout to end-2014. €300-400bn, skewing to upper end of that range. <a href=\"http://t.co/Q1lGSbbE\" title=\"http://twitpic.com/aasp0v\">twitpic.com/aasp0v</a></p>&mdash; P M (@Pawelmorski) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/Pawelmorski/status/227327150544535552\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-23T08:59:50+00:00\">July 23, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure>  <p>And here's the envelope, showing the cost of paying off Spain's maturing debt, plus the coupon payments on existing loans, plus its deficit, plus the cost of debt issued by its regions:<br /><br /></p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-7fcc31ab-546a-4962-b1a4-bf64d60e16c0\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/7/23/1343037956795/-460.png\" alt=\"Back-of-the-envelope calculation of Spanish bailout\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Back-of-the-envelope calculation of Spanish bailout</figcaption> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d1bac95cbd01cfadc5b02\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>The Spanish economy minister, <strong>Luis de Guindos</strong>, has attempted to calm the markets this morning by declaring that Spain will not need a full bailout.</p> <p>Speaking in Madrid a few minutes ago, <strong>De Guindos</strong> said Spain will not follow Greece, Ireland and Portugal into seeking a financial aid package. Asked if a bailout would be needed, he replied:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Absolutely not.</p> </blockquote> <p>Mind you, finance ministers <strong>always</strong> deny that a bailout is imminent, as CNBC anchor <a href=\"http://www.twitter.com/@RossWestgate%20\">Ross Westgate</a> points out:</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/RossWestgate/status/227334037008707584\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>I wonder if the Spanish Fin Min ruling out a full Sovereign bailout is like a Football Chairman saying the manager has his full support</p>&mdash; Ross Westgate (@RossWestgate) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/RossWestgate/status/227334037008707584\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-23T09:27:12+00:00\">July 23, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d1994b579b8fa1c624326\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">GREEK EXIT FEARS MOUNT</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Today's selloff has also been driven by fears that Germany has lost patience with Greece, and is prepared to see the country leave the eurozone.</p> <p>German economy minister <strong>Philipp R&ouml;sler </strong>sparked new speculation of an imminent <strong>Grexit</strong> yesterday, by declaring that he was \"very sceptical\" that Greece can hit the targets laid out under its second bailout.</p> <p><strong>R&ouml;sler</strong> went on to reject the idea that Athens could be granted more time (as Antonis Samaras, the Greek prime minister, hopes), saying:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>What&rsquo;s emerging is that Greece will probably not be able to fulfil its conditions &hellip;</p> <p>What is clear: if Greece doesn&rsquo;t fulfil those conditions, then there can be no more payments.</p> </blockquote> <p>No more payments = exit and default?</p> <p><strong>R&ouml;sler then declared that \"for many experts &hellip; a Greek exit from the eurozone has long since lost its horror.\"</strong></p> <p>That claim has been swiftly rebutted by Paul Donovan of UBS, who told clients this morning that this is \"good grounds to start being terrified\":</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>If policy makers have lost a sense of terror, it seems likely they have lost their understanding of economic reality.</p> </blockquote> <p>R&ouml;sler's comments could be dismissed as another bout of voter-friendly tough-talk from a party whose popularity has fallen in recent months. <a href=\"http://www.spiegel.de/wirtschaft/unternehmen/euro-krise-iwf-will-griechenland-hilfen-stoppen-a-845718.html\">Except for an article in Der Spiegel which confidently predicts that the International Monetary Fund will pull the plug on Greece soon</a>.</p> <p>Der Spiegel claims that IMF officials have told the EU that it is \"no longer willing to provide additional funds for Greece help\".</p> <p>So, it argues, European leaders will refuse any extra help for Greece just as soon as the European Stability Mechanism is in place. That could be September (when Germany's highest court rules whether the ESM breaches German law).</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d151695cbd01cfadc5b01\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>As this photo shows, Spanish citizens continued to protest against Mariano Rajoy's austerity package over the weekend:</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-388d431c-c34e-4f8a-bc5b-fcbd97ba1a8b\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/7/23/1343034210352/d55972b2-d934-402b-9e5b-4c033aab8b92-460.jpeg\" alt=\"Anti-austerity protests in Madrid, 21 July 2012.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Protesters demonstrate in Madrid against Spain's near 25% unemployment rate as well as austerity measures introduced by the government. (Andres Kudacki/AP Photo)</figcaption> </figure>  <p>Some people had walked from Spain's regions to take part. The protest converged outside the ministry for employment, where demonstrators banged drums and chanted: \"Unemployed, wake up!\", before heading to Madrid's central square, Puerta del Sol.</p> <p>As <a href=\"http://uk.reuters.com/article/2012/07/21/uk-spain-protests-idUKBRE86K0HH20120721\">Reuters reports</a>:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Several hundred people journeyed on foot from the southern region of Andalucia, which has one of the worst unemployment rates in Spain, and from northern Catalonia and other areas in an attempt to highlight the plight of the unemployed in recession-hit Spain, where almost one in four is without a job.</p> <p>\"I joined the Barcelona-Madrid march, the march for dignity, and I'm protesting to get a decent job ... and against the cuts and what they are doing to citizens,\" said Tania Faturechi, 30.</p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d0bffb579b8fa1c624322\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Yet another reason to worry &ndash; the cost of insuring Spanish debt has spiked to a record high.</strong></p> <p><strong>Markit</strong> is reporting that the cost of a Spanish credit default swap (which pays out if Spain defaults on its loans) has jumped to 630 basis points (from 603 on Friday). <strong>That means it would cost &euro;630,000 a year to insure &euro;10m of Spanish five-year debt.</strong></p> <p>Other eurozone CDS contracts have also jumped this morning:</p> <p><strong>France: 182bp, up 12</strong></p> <p><strong>Italy: 555bp, up 29</strong></p> <p><strong>Ireland: 580bp, up 20</strong></p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d090a95cbd01cfadc5afe\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>The Bank of Spain has added to the gloom this morning, predicting that the Spanish recession deepened in the last three months.</p> <p>In its latest forecasts, the central bank estimated that Spanish GDP fell by 0.4% in the second quarter of 2012, a sharper fall than the 0.3% contraction recorded in Q1. That would mean Spain's economy was 1% smaller than a year ago.</p> <p>According to Reuters, the Bank's deputy governor is arguing now that the solution is \"<em><strong>more cuts, more reforms, and new mechanisms to integrate the eurozone</strong></em>\". But will market patience last?</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d07e9b579b8fa1c624320\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Italy is also feeling the pressure this morning, with its 10-year bond yield jumping to 6.4%. That's still much lower than the record levels seen during the last days (hours!) of Silvio Berlusconi's regime in November 2011.</p> <p>But interestingly, it's higher than the Irish 10-year yield of 6.26% this morning.</p> <p><strong>So bailed-out Ireland (midway through a painful fiscal consolidation plan) is being treated as a safer bet than Italy (where Mario Monti is battling to push economic reforms through before he steps down in 2013).</strong></p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d053795cbd01cfadc5afd\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>There's not a single riser in the FTSE 100 right now, as the selloff deepens (down 82 points). Leading the slide are <strong>Aviva</strong> (-4.1%) and <strong>Royal Bank of Scotland</strong> (-3.8%).</p> <p>Spanish* banks are also taking a hammering, with <strong>Bankia</strong> suffering the most (down 8%):</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/LemaSabachthani/status/227310175248334849\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>**Banco Popular -4.90%, Banco Sabadell -4.95%, Banco Santander -3.80%, Bankia -8.00%, Bankinter - 5.41%, BBVA -4.92%%; IBEX35 <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search/%2523Spain\">#Spain</a></p>&mdash; Eloi Eloi (@LemaSabachthani) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/LemaSabachthani/status/227310175248334849\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-23T07:52:23+00:00\">July 23, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure>  <p><em>* - not Italian, as I initially wrote :(</em></p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500d020cb579b8fa1c62431f\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">HOW SPANISH YIELDS CLIMBED TO TODAY'S RECORD HIGHS</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Spain's 10-year bond yields remain firmly in the danger zone this morning, at over 7.5% (up from 7.275% on Friday night).</p> <p>7% is typically seen as the level at which a country's borrowing costs becomes unsustainable. This graph shows how Spanish 10-year yields are now higher than in November (when the eurozone was rocked by the collapse of the Greek government).</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-eee5d8d1-b645-4b7c-ab1c-551cc70c5e09\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/7/23/1343029383954/-460.jpeg\" alt=\"Spanish 10-year bond yields, to 23 July 2012.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Spanish 10-year bond yields, to 23 July 2012. Source: Reuters/Tradeweb.</figcaption> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500cfea6b579b8fa1c62431e\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>The euro has fallen to a fresh set of lows against other currencies this morning</strong>, as fears swirl that Spain will be locked out of the financial markets.</p> <p>Against the yen, the euro fell by more than 1% to just 94.27 yen, the single currencies lowest level since November 2000.</p> <p>The euro has also continued its slide against the US dollar, hitting $1.2085, and it's down at a a new nine and a half-year low against the Norwegian krone.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500cfbaf95cbd01cfadc5afc\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">Stock markets fall sharply</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-4726242d-7195-40f2-87f5-4ce23ebe4d34\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/7/23/1343032685149/575f436d-bf89-450a-aef1-e3c8747c654b-460.jpeg\" alt=\"A TV cameraman films an electronic stock board of a securities firm in Tokyo as Japan's Nikkei fell 161.55 points to close at 8,508.32 Monday, July 23, 2012.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>A TV cameraman films an electronic stock board of a securities firm in Tokyo, where the Nikkei fell 161.55 points to close at 8,508.32. (Koji Sasahara/AP)</figcaption> </figure>  <p>European stock markets have fallen sharply in early trading (following Asian markets), with Spain and Italy leading the way. Here's a roundup:</p> <p><strong>FTSE 100: down 76 points at 5577, -1.35%</strong></p> <p><strong>Spanish IBEX: down 149 points at 6095, - 2.4%</strong></p> <p><strong>Italian FTSE MIB: down 330 points at 12737. -2.5%</strong></p> <p><strong>French CAC: -1.5%</strong></p> <p><strong>German DAX: -1.27%</strong></p> <p><strong><br />Michael Hewson,</strong> of CMC Markets, says that fears over Spain's solvency are alarming traders, who fear that the Madrid government is losing its battle to avoid a full-scale bailout.</p> <p><strong>Hewson</strong> explains:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p><br />With voters pushing back on the government&rsquo;s austerity plans, the room for manoeuvre of the Spanish government is diminishing by the day as the economy continues to deteriorate under a combination of rising unemployment and rising bad loans.</p> </blockquote> <p>Should more regions, such as Catalonia, seek aid (see 8.14am), it will be \"pretty much nailed on that the Spanish government will then eventually need a bailout itself\", he adds.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500cf9f0b579b8fa1c62431d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>The surge in Spanish bond yields this morning comes after Murcia became the second Spanish region to ask for state aid.</p> <p>Murcia admitted on Sunday it will seek up to &euro;300m from the central government, two days after <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/20/spain-crisis-eurozone-valencia\">Valencia made its own plea for help</a>.</p> <p>Other regions are expected to follow, with Catalonia reportedly unable to pay the interest on &euro;48bn of borrowings.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2012/jul/22/markets-fear-for-spanish-economy\">As we reported last night</a>:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Several others among Spain's 17 semi-autonomous regions are expected to follow. They include the two biggest regions, Catalonia and Andalucia, as well as central Castilla La Mancha.</p> <p>...</p> <p>The coming wave of regional bailouts may add further pressure to Spain's bond yields as they threaten to spiral out of control and drive Spain towards a full rescue.</p> </blockquote> <p>Analysts have long feared that Spain's autonomous regions are in worse financial shape than officially admitted. This cuts to the heart of the concerns over Spain &ndash; as any plan devised by Madrid requires the co-operation of the regions.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500cf7c9b579b8fa1c62431c\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">SPANISH YIELDS SPARK ALARM</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>This morning's nervy selloff has also driven up the yield on Spanish two-year bonds to a new euro-era record of <strong>6.124%</strong>.</p> <p>That's an eye-wateringly high rate (in comparison, UK two-year gilts are trading with a yield of just <strong>0.091%</strong>).</p> <p>These yields in the bond market are a good indication of how much it would cost Spain to borrow from international investors. At this morning's yields, Madrid would effectively be shut out of the markets.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/chrisadamsmkts/status/227287185127260160\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Spain won't be able to sell 10 yr debt at these rates (7.368 pct). If short term rates keep rising, it will struggle to refinance at all</p>&mdash; Chris Adams (@chrisadamsmkts) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/chrisadamsmkts/status/227287185127260160\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-23T06:21:02+00:00\">July 23, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500cf4ec95cbd01cfadc5afb\" class=\"block is-summary\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-10-24T17:19:12.087+01:00\">5.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">The Agenda</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Good morning, and welcome to <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/debt-crisis\">our rolling coverage of the eurozone financial crisis</a>.</p> <p>It's early, but there are already worrying signs in the financial markets that the crisis is escalating:</p> <p><strong>Spanish government bonds have fallen to their lowest levels since the euro was created. This pushed the yield (effectively the interest rate) on its 10-year bonds to a new record high of 7.513% &ndash; further into the zone where borrowing costs are unsustainable.</strong></p> <p>The selloff was triggered by fears that Spain's autonomous regions are in deep trouble and need financial help, threatening the prime minister Mariano Rajoy's efforts to battle the Spanish economic crisis.</p> <p><br />Meanwhile, over in Greece, the government is still struggling to meet the demands of its international lenders. The Troika returns tomorrow, and will want evidence that Athens is meeting its targets. But with the Greek government pleading for more time, the talk this morning is that a Grexit is back on the agenda.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-07-22/greece-back-at-center-of-euro-crisis-as-exit-talk-resurfaces.html\">As Bloomberg puts it</a> &ndash;</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Greece retakes its position at the heart of the European dent crisis this week as its creditors assess how far off course the country is from bailout targets, raising again the specter of its exit from the euro.</p> </blockquote> <p>City traders are predicting that stock markets will fall this morning, with the FTSE 100 being called down around 50 points.</p> <p><br />Also coming up this morning: the latest Spanish mortgage data (<strong>8am BST</strong>), bond auctions from Germany and France (<strong>morning</strong>), and the eurozone consumer confidence data for June (<strong>3pm BST</strong>).</p> </div>   </div>","headline":"Eurozone crisis live: Markets tumble amid fears over Spain and Greece","trailText":"<p>Spanish and Italian stocks were down almost 5% this morning after bond yields hit dangerous levels</p>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2010/11/30/1291113270072/Eurozone-in-crisis-003.jpg","wordcount":"4571","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"393456446","allowUgc":"false","internalComposerCode":"524ecbd0e4b0b103eb47f53e","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Graeme Wearden and Nick Fletcher","displayRelativeTimes":"false","internalPageCode":"1777161","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2012-07-26T06:55:00+00:00"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/business/2012/jul/23/eurozone-crisis-spain-bond-yields1","tags":[{"id":"business/debt-crisis","webTitle":"Eurozone crisis","type":"keyword","sectionId":"business","sectionName":"Business","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/debt-crisis","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/business/debt-crisis","references":[]},{"id":"business/series/eurozone-crisis-live","webTitle":"Eurozone crisis live","description":"On our daily blog we report on the turmoil in the bond, stock and currency markets - as well as the political dramas at the heart of the eurozone crisis.","type":"series","sectionId":"business","sectionName":"Business","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/series/eurozone-crisis-live","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianap