slide below the $1.21 mark against the US dollar. (Alex Domanski/Reuters)","mediaId":"gu-fc-e9baf6d7-9e21-44cb-a068-952031c31c58","width":"140"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"Eurozone crisis live: Fitch raises Greece out of default - Tuesday 13 March","webPublicationDate":"2012-03-13T17:47:00Z","sectionName":"Business","sectionId":"business","id":"business/2012/mar/13/eurozone-crisis-greek-deal-spain-austerity","fields":{"secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Politics/Pix/pictures/2012/1/3/1325585974887/Euro-notes-and-coins-003.jpg","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/365z8","standfirst":"• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/13/eurozone-crisis-greek-deal-spain-austerity#block-22\">Athens denies needing yet more austerity</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/13/eurozone-crisis-greek-deal-spain-austerity#block-18\">Spain claims victory over deficit</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/13/eurozone-crisis-greek-deal-spain-austerity#block-27\">Stock markets close higher</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/13/eurozone-crisis-greek-deal-spain-austerity#block-12\">Euro taskforce reaches Athens</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/13/eurozone-crisis-greek-deal-spain-austerity#block-3\">Cyprus downgraded to junk</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/13/eurozone-crisis-greek-deal-spain-austerity#block-4\">Today's agenda</a>","hasStoryPackage":"true","lastModified":"2014-05-20T22:51:38Z","body":"<!-- Block 31 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">5.45pm:</span> I'm afraid I've got to drop the blog for the day now. Thanks for reading, and for your comments and assistance. We'll be back tomorrow.</p><p><strong>Goodnight!</strong></p><!-- Block 30 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">5.21pm:</span> Greeks have been told that as of the end of the month all civil servants will be appraised by other senior civil servants and \"experts\" in the private sector.</p><p>From Athens, Helena Smith has the details:<br /> </p><blockquote><p>The monitoring of the performance of civil servants was announced after Horst Reichenbach, the visiting head of the EU task force created with the express purpose of reforming Greece's public administration, held a series of meetings in Athens with top government officials.</p><p>In a country whose public sector is the antithesis of meritocracy the move is bound to be met with howls of protest. But EU officials say it is the only way of turning Greece's dysfunctional civil service around. For safety's sake it was announced that the task force will be supervising the monitoring!</p></blockquote><p>We wrote about Horst Reichenbach's visit to Greece this morning (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/13/eurozone-crisis-greek-deal-spain-austerity#block-12\">see 11.06am</a>), explaining how he has been playing the \"good cop\".</p><p><strong>Helena</strong> continues:</p><blockquote><p>Officials announced that as of this week pensioners receiving state handouts will ALSO be counted. Readers will recall that until recently when a census of civil servants was ordered by the previous socialist government, no one was sure how many many public sector employees were on the payroll. The discovery, made by former finance minister Michalis Papaconstantinou, was one of the first signs for mandarins in Brussels that something was rotten in the state of Greece - and it wasn't only its mountain of debt. </p><p>There are currently thought to be around 800,000 Greek civil servants.</p><p>But to end on a good note. Greeks appear to be delighted with the choice of Eleftheria Eleftheriou the crooner who will be representing the nation in this year's Eurovision Song contest with the song Aphrodisiac. </p></blockquote><!-- Block 29 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">5.05pm:</span> I reckon that <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/13/eurozone-crisis-greek-deal-spain-austerity#block-28\">this</a> is the first time that Fitch has upgraded Greece's credit rating since October 2003, when it raised Athens to A+ (there's a full list of Fitch rating moves <a href=\"http://www.google.co.uk/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cts=1331659540671&amp;sqi=2&amp;ved=0CCUQFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.fitchratings.com%2Fweb_content%2Fratings%2Fsovereign_ratings_history.xls&amp;ei=CoNfT56cM6X80QX9mL2rBw&amp;usg=AFQjCNGTQwy2GiqEuwksosJStEpnVydZBg\">online in a pdf, here</a>)</p><p>Financial journalists are joking tonight that they've never had the chance to write upgrade and Greece in the same tweet before.</p><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Fitch upgrades Greece to B-. Haven't used \"upgrade\" and \"Greece\" in the same tweet, ever.</p><p>— Charles Forelle (@charlesforelle) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/charlesforelle/status/179610460209954817\" data-datetime=\"2012-03-13T16:50:45+00:00\">March 13, 2012</a></p></blockquote><!-- Block 28 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387297103'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/5/12/1305203064788/Live-blog-news-flash-001.jpg' alt='Live blog: news flash newsflash' width='40' height='40' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">4.52pm:</span> Breaking news -- <strong>Fitch has upgraded Greece to B- with a stable outlook, from Restricted Default, following its bond exchange.</strong></p><p>In a statement, Fitch said that Greece's debt service profile has been \"significantly improved\" now that €100bn has been wiped off its debt pile. It warned, though, that \"significant and material default risk remains\".</p><p>B- is only the sixth highest junk rating, classed as 'highly speculative' on Fitch scale.</p><p>Here's some key quotes from the statement:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p> In Fitch's view, there is a limited margin of safety for debt service on the new securities over a 12 to 24 month horizon, reflected in the Stable Outlook.</p><p>Post-default, debt service should be moderate. The effective interest rate on public debt is estimated to have fallen to less than 4% from 5.5%, while substantive amortisation payments have been pushed out to 2020 and beyond. Nonetheless, the capacity for continued payment remains vulnerable to deterioration in the political and economic environment.</p><p>Fitch expects the new EU-IMF programme will be fully funded (ie. not reliant on Greece regaining access to term finance from the market), in contrast to the first Greek Loan Facility, providing a limited margin of safety for bondholders.</p><p>While it is possible to discern a downward trajectory of the public debt/GDP ratio to around 120% by 2020 as targeted by the EU/IMF, this outcome is very sensitive to assumptions regarding the implementation of fiscal austerity and economic growth.</p><p>The current government has completed a long list of 'prior actions'. However, their implementation is likely to prove very challenging for any administration, while Greece's ability to sustain primary surpluses of 4.5% of GDP from 2014 onwards is untested.</p></blockquote><p><a href=\"http://www.fitchratings.com/creditdesk/press_releases/detail.cfm?pr_id=745069&amp;origin=home\">The full statement is online here.</a></p><!-- Block 27 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">4.33pm:</span> European stock markets have just closed strongly, with many indexes closing at their highest levels since last July.</p><p>Here's the numbers:</p><p><strong>FTSE 100:</strong> up 1.07% , or 63 points, at 5955<br /><strong>Germany's DAX:</strong> up 1.37% at 6995<br /><strong>France's CAC:</strong> up 1.72% at 3550</p><p><strong>Yusuf Heusen</strong>, sales trader at IG Index, commented:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Expectations that today would be quiet have been dashed as US markets hit new post-crisis highs despite the presence of a Fed meeting on today's agenda. US retail sales rose at their fastest rate for five months, as US consumers took heart from the improved employment landscape and returned to their shopping malls with new determination to spend.</p></blockquote><!-- Block 26 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">4.16pm:</span> Regular reader <strong><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/ballymichael\">Ballymichael</a></strong> points out that the memorandum of understanding on Greek economic policy mentioned earlier (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/13/eurozone-crisis-greek-deal-spain-austerity?commentpage=5#block-22\">see 2.29pm</a>) is now online, and can be seen <a href=\"http://www.scribd.com/doc/81233785/Greece%E2%80%94Memorandum-of-Understanding-on-Specific-Economic-Policy-Conditionality-9-Feb-2012\">here</a>. Thanks BM.....</p><!-- Block 25 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">4.01pm:</span> Greece has announced this afternoon that it expects to receive <strong>a total of €172bn of external aid between now and 2015.</strong></p><p>Finance minister <strong>Evengelos Venizeloz</strong> said in a statement that Greece will receive the €130bn aid package that has finally been agreed after months of haggling, plus around €34.5bn currently untapped from its first rescue deal. It also hopes that the IMF might extend an €8.2bn loan in 2015 (on top of the IMF's contribution to the €130bn package).</p><p>Speaking of Venizelos....</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387297104'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2012/3/13/1331655449467/Greeces-finance-minister--007.jpg' alt='Greece's finance minister Evangelos Venizelos, speaks during a Pasok conference.' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Vote for me! Greece's finance minister Evangelos Venizelos speaks during a Pasok conference last weekend. Photograph: Kostas Tsironis/AP</figcaption></figure><p>.... the finance minister is now on track to become the next leader of the socialist Pasok party, after emerging as the only candidate to replace George Papandreou.</p><p>Last weekend, Venizelos apologised for the turmoil that has gripped Greece and warned: \"The crisis is not over, the key is work, work, work\".</p><p>Venizelos also had yoghurt thrown at him during a Pasok conference, by a disgruntled pensioner. This is part of the growing phenomenon of <em>γιαούρτωμα</em> or '<em>Yoghurtification</em>'</p><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/#!/KallergisK\">Kostas Kallergis</a>, a freelance journalist based in Athens, has written an interesting article on this -- <strong><a href=\"http://whenthecrisishitthefan.com/2012/03/10/on-yogurts-as-a-form-of-political-protest-in-greece/\">On yogurts as a form of political protest in Greece</a></strong>.</p><p>It all dates back to the \"Teddy Boys\", would you believe?</p><!-- Block 24 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">3.39pm:</span> One interesting theme today is finance ministers insisting that the Greek debt swap was slightly more successful than hoped.</p><p>Both <strong>Wolfgang Schäuble</strong> of Germany and <strong>Jan Kees de Jager</strong> of the Netherlands have said this afternoon that Greece's debt/GDP ratio is now on track to fall below 120% of GDP by 2020 (the target set in the bailout agreement).</p><p>De Jager told Dutch radio that:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>All in all the bonds swap is now already more successful than expected. This means that the debt sustainability as compiled by the IMF - taking into account all risks and assumptions that come with it of course - is a bit more positive than was expected.</p></blockquote><p>However, many economists still question whether the assumptions made in the Greek aid plan still hold up.</p><!-- Block 23 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387297105'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Travel/Pix/pictures/2007/01/19/Budapest2.jpg' alt='Budapest, Hungary' width='220' height='132' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Budapest, Hungary, which faces losing €495m of structural aid.</figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">2.55pm:</span> European finance ministers have agreed to suspend almost half a billion euros in aid from Hungary, as a penalty for not hitting its deficit reduction targets.</p><p>But Hungary could still dodge the sanction, if it can prove in June that it can get its fiscal deficit below 3% of GDP by 2013.</p><p>The decision was taken at today's Ecofin meeting in Brussels, where officials speak of a \"compromise\" over Hungary.</p><p>Hungary, which has clashed with the rest of the EU establishment repeatedly over the past couple of years, is on track for a 3% deficit in 2012, and 3.6% in 2013. </p><p><strong>The funds in question are meant to support economic development in Europe's poorer regions, so there is a certain irony in Europe deciding to withhold them because a country's economy is in worse shape than hoped. </strong></p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2012/feb/22/hungary-faces-loss-of-aid-eu-budget\">Last month, Olli Rehn criticised Hungary for running a deficit above 3% for almost every year since 2004.</a> Budapest pointed out that it actually got annual borrowing below 3% last year, but Rehn dismissed this achievement as a one-off.</p><p>This is the first time that Europe has decided to withhold structural aid in this way.</p><!-- Block 22 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">2.29pm:</span> A report today <a href=\"http://uk.reuters.com/article/2012/03/13/uk-eurozone-greece-austerity-idUKBRE82C0KY20120313\">claiming that Greece must slash government spending by a further 5.5% of GDP in 2013 and 2014 to meet agreed fiscal targets</a> is being dismissed as <strong>\"no news\"</strong> by government officials in Athens.</p><p><strong>Helena Smith</strong>, our correspondent in Greece, reports:</p><blockquote><p>The Greek government spokesman Pandelis Kapsis poured cold water on the exclusive run by Reuters outlining the tough measures that Athens will have to take to reduce government spending in the years ahead.</p><p>The news agency, in a dispatch out of Brussels citing a leaked Compliance Report from the European Commission, said Greece \"will have to slash a further 5.5% of GDP in government spending in 2013 and 2014 to meet agreed fiscal targets underpinning the second international bailout for Athens.\" </p><p>\"Current projections,\" it said quoting the report,  \"reveal large fiscal gaps in 2013-14,\" adding that the shortfall for the two years totalled 5.5%. </p><p>The gap meant that Greece would have to take \"substantial additional expenditure cuts\" when it updated its medium term budget in May 2012.</p><p>\"All this, including the necessary measures to cover the 5.5% reduction are in the memorandum of understanding that was voted in parliament two weeks ago by both parties [backing technocrat prime minister's Lucas Papademos' interim government],\" said Kapsis. \"This is not news. We know it already,\" he insisted, adding that fresh austerity measures, also referred to in the MOU, would be \"decided by June.\" </p></blockquote><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387297106'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2012/2/13/1329154607096/Protesters-pass-by-a-burn-007.jpg' alt='Protesters pass by a burning cinema in Athens' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>A cinema aflame in Athens on February 12, 2012, a night when Greek MPs voted on its austerity plan. Photograph: Kostas Tsironis/AP</figcaption></figure><p>The passage of that bill, is still a burning memory for most Greeks, Helena adds. It prompted one of the biggest protests since the crisis began, and running battles that eupted into an orgy of violence as thousands of hooded youths went on the rampage torching buildings, shops, banks and cars.</p><!-- Block 21 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387297107'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2010/05/21/Marketup.gif' alt='Live blog - market up' width='40' height='40' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">2.15pm:</span> A solid start to trading in New York saw the S&amp;P 500 hit its highest intraday level since June 2008. Three month's before the collapse of Lehman Brothers.</p><p>The <strong>Dow Jones</strong> also started positively, up 48 points at 13008. Investors appeared relaxed about the eurozone situation, especially after German investor confidence came in higher (see <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/13/eurozone-crisis-greek-deal-spain-austerity#block-15\">12.21pm</a>)</p><p>Data showing that US retail sales grew at their fastest pace in five months also cheered Wall Street. Americans increased their spending on motor vehicles last month, despite fears of a new oil spike.</p><!-- Block 20 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">2.07pm:</span> The full text of Mario Draghi's speech on \"Competitiveness of the euro area and within the euro area\" is now <a href=\"http://www.ecb.europa.eu/press/key/date/2012/html/sp120313.en.html\">online here</a>.</p><p>Here's a flavour from the speech, which he gave in Paris this morning;</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>In times of severe financial constraints, there is no other choice than to address the structural losses in competitiveness in an urgent and decisive manner.</p><p>What monetary policy can do for competitiveness is to ensure price stability in the euro area, reducing risk premia and making sure that all the transmission channels of the monetary impulse do work.</p><p>I would add that the markets clearly understand that.</p></blockquote><!-- Block 19 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">1.45pm:</span> In the reader comments below, <strong><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/westpier\">westpier</a></strong> asks whether anyone knows anything about <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/comment-permalink/15124910\">a claim that</a> the Spanish sports minister has just exempted some of the great football clubs from paying €1.3bn tax debt.</p><p>I didn't know about this, and then this info popped up on AP:</p><blockquote><p>Spanish football clubs owe the government €752m ($982 million) in unpaid back taxes, according to figures released Tuesday.<br />The United Left party says figures provided by the government show an increase of nearly 150 million ($195 million) in unpaid taxes over the past four years, with topflight clubs making up nearly half a billion euros ($653 million) of the overall figure. At least six top division clubs are already in bankruptcy protection.<br />The numbers were released after the United Left, a communist party led coalition, submitted a written request to parliament for the information.</p></blockquote><p>If anyone knows more, do let us know in the comments below....</p><!-- Block 18 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">1.35pm:</span> Spain has agreed to the Eurogroup's demand that it cuts its deficit to 5.3% of GDP this year. In fact, the Madrid government is treating the move as a triumph.</p><p><strong>Luis de Guindos</strong> declared today that the new target would be accepted by the govenment, even though it's tougher than its own goal of a 5.8% deficit. He told reporters:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Spain is completely committed to the budget adjustment.</p></blockquote><p>...and added that Madrid should be able to find an extra 0.5% of cuts without \"significantly\" hitting growth or employment levels.</p><p>Spain, of course, can ill-afford extra pain on either count. The jobless rate is already tipped to hit 24.3% this year, with the economy expected to shrink until the second half of 2012.</p><p>Still, there's an upbeat feeling coming out of Spain today, with foreign minister José Manuel García-Margallo apparently telling local radio that;</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The Spanish government has won this battle.</p></blockquote><p>(<a href=\"http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/8d188386-6d05-11e1-ab1a-00144feab49a.html#axzz1ozYNuLtd\">via the FT</a>).</p><!-- Block 17 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387297108'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2010/5/5/1273051870749/Live-blog---euro-001.jpg' alt='Live blog - euro' width='40' height='40' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">1.09pm:</span> The euro has fallen to a one month low against the dollar, hitting $1.3048 in the last few minutes...</p><!-- Block 16 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387297109'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2012/3/13/1331645053032/ECB-President-Draghi-deli-001.jpg' alt='ECB President Draghi delivers a speech during the \"Competitiveness Challenge\" meeting in Paris' width='220' height='300' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Mario Draghi, delivering a speech during the \"Competitiveness Challenge\" meeting in Paris today. Photograph: Benoit Tessier/Reuters</figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">12.54pm:</span> ECB president <strong>Mario Draghi</strong> and <strong>Jens Weidmann</strong> of the Bundesbank (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/13/eurozone-crisis-greek-deal-spain-austerity#block-10\">mentioned at 10.18am</a>) have been playing down their differences today (despite being almost 300 miles apart).</p><p>At an event in Paris <strong>Draghi</strong>, the man who has handed €1tn of cheap loans to European banks since replacing Jean-Claude Trichet last November, insisted he was \"committed\" to maintaining his predecessor's commitment to price stability. That could be a signal that another cut in eurozone interest rates is not close.</p><p>Draghi also gave European leaders another signal that they need to take advantage of the window created by the ECB. He warned that:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Unless structural reforms are undertaken, it will be difficult to keep the eurozone together.</p></blockquote><p>In Frankfurt, meanwhile, Weidmann denied being at odds with Draghi. He said there was no need to unwind the ECB's  \"non-standard measures\" immediately. But he wants clear discussions of how and when to exit these measures, and insisted:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>I would describe my personal relationship [with Draghi]....as very good.</p></blockquote><!-- Block 15 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387297110'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2010/5/5/1273067880031/Live-blog---Germany-flag-001.jpg' alt='Live blog - Germany flag' width='60' height='40' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">12.21pm:</span> Hopes that Germany will avoid recession were bolstered by the news today that German investor confidence rose for the fourth month in a row, hitting the highest level since mid-2010.</p><p>The ZEW institute said its confidence index rose to 22.3 points in March from 5.4 in February, a better performance than the rise to around 12 that economists had expected and the best since June 2010.</p><p>ZEW president <strong>Wolfgang Franz</strong> said:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>In Germany, due to the good employment situation, domestic demand is likely to continue to stimulate growth.</p></blockquote><!-- Block 14 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">11.55am:</span> A remarkable photograph of John-Claude Juncker appearing to throttle Spain's finance minister is circulating today.</p><p>The picture, taken in Brussels yesterday, shows the the eurogroup president with both hands around the neck of Luis de Guindos. As you can see:</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387297111'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2012/3/13/1331638812451/Jean-Claude-Juncker-right-007.jpg' alt='Jean-Claude Juncker, right, puts his hands on the neck of Spain's Economy Minister Luis de Guindos.' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Photograph: Isopix / Rex Features</figcaption></figure><p>That's from our photo library, along with photos of the pair holding serious discussions afterwards (with de Guindos looking a little pinker than usual)</p><p><strong>UPDATE:</strong> <a href=\"http://www.20minutos.tv/video/wyACIO16-peculiar-recibimiento-de-juncker-a-guindos/0/\">This video clip</a> records the moment happen. Contrary to my earlier suggestion, it was a momentary event (the press snappers just fired off plenty of pictures of it). Many thanks to reader <strong>Michael Bimmler</strong> for finding it.</p><p><strong>Open Europe</strong>, the thinktank, say the image could be an apt metaphor, saying:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The eurozone chokes Spain....the fiscal compact in action?</p></blockquote><p>Older readers may remember the classic joke about how every time prime minister Harold Macmillan returned from a journey abroad Rab Butler was at the bottom of the steps, ready to grip him warmly by the throat (Butler having been defeated in a leadership battle by the future 1st Earl of Stockton).</p><!-- Block 13 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">11.21am:</span> Looking around the eurozone, there is more evidence that Ireland's property market remains in the doldrums.</p><p>Average house prices have now fallen to just 68%  of their value during the Celtic Tiger boom, according to a Goodbody's survey released today.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387297112'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/2/18/1298047334982/A-deserted-housing-develo-007.jpg' alt='A deserted housing development, in Mullingar, Ireland' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>A deserted housing development, in Mullingar, Ireland.  Photograph: Cathal McNaughton/Reuters</figcaption></figure><p>Potential buyers also face a credit squeeze -- with mortgage lending levels back to what they were in 1971.</p><p><strong>Henry McDonald</strong> reports from Dublin:</p><blockquote><p>The average price of Irish residential property sold recently at five Allsop Space Auctions held in Dublin over the past year was €145,000. <br />Goodbody's report found that tight credit conditions from banks still coping with toxic loans, an oversupply of empty properties and low domestic demand are the main factors in keeping the country's property market depressed.   </p><p>The property crash in the Republic is also having a knock on effect on house prices north of the border in Northern Ireland. Northern Ireland are down by as much as 70% from their peak,  the Royal Institution for Chartered Surveyors said today.</p><p>There are fears that once so-called NAMA properties (houses, apartments and offices taken over by the Irish state from bankrupt speculators and their banks) flood the market in Northern Ireland house prices could fall even further. </p></blockquote><p>Another sign that the crisis has a long way to play out....</p><!-- Block 12 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">11.06am:</span> Athens has been 'welcoming' <strong>Horst Reichenbach</strong>, head of the European Commission special task force for Greece. who arrived last night.</p><p><strong>Helena Smith</strong>, our correspondent, says <strong>Reichenbach</strong> has been busy telling Greek TV channels that \"Greece will succeed.\"</p><p>Helena writes:</p><blockquote><p>The soft-spoken German has gone out of his way to tell Greeks he is not here \"to exercise power but to support the country's administration.\" \"I am sure Greece will make it,\" he told the state-run NET TV channel.</p><p>Key to development and growth and thus Greece's economic rejuvenation is the \"extra liquidity\" that will come with the recapitalisation of the country's banking system to help boost its cash-starved marketplace and crumbling productive base of small and medium sized enterprises. </p><p>\"The next great task [after the debt relief] is to recapitalise the Greek banks and I hope everything will go smoothly,\" he told Mega TV.  <br /> <br />Readers will recall that Greece has experienced a capital flight in excess of €60bn since the crisis first erupted in December 2009, with just under €20bn of that amount being squirreled into accounts abroad - mostly in the UK.   <br /> <br />The European Financial Stability Facility weighed in with the same message Monday night announcing that Athens is on line to receive €48bn in loans from the eurozone for the recapitalization of its banks.</p></blockquote><p>Reichenbach has often been portrayed as playing 'good cop' to Greece. The 'bad cop' are the EU and IMF inspectors regularly deployed to Greece to monitor its public finances. <br /> <br />But how long Greeks will put up with his charm offensive is far from sure, Helena says:</p><blockquote><p>The media is also full of reports that the EU task force is about to dispatch scores of Germans to \"take over\" the state's leaky tax collective system and dozens of French experts to oversee its problem-plagued public administration. </p></blockquote><!-- Block 11 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">10.47am:</span> Just in, European finance ministers meeting in Brussels have given their approval to the \"adjusted measures for Greece\" (ie, its second rescue package).</p><p>That means that all 27 finance ministers from across the EU have given the green light, after last night's vote of approval from the eurozone.</p><!-- Block 10 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387297113'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2012/1/17/1326799792668/Bundesbank-Germany-005.jpg' alt='Bundesbank, Germany' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Photograph: imagebroker / Alamy</figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">10.18am:</span> Profits at Germany's central bank have more than halved, as it prepares to suffer the cost of the eurozone crisis.</p><p>The Bundesbank reported that profits in 2011 fell to €643m, from €2.2bn in 2010, as it rasied its risk provisions (covering potential losses on credit, exchange rate swaps and gold reserves) by €4.1bn.</p><p>The figures show that the Bundesbank is increasingly concerned that central banks will eventually pay a high price for the eurocrisis. President Jens Weidmann said:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The main reason for the decline in profitability is the increase in risk provisions.</p><p>The counterparty credit risks arising from the government bond purchase programme and refinancing business have increased perceptibly as a result of the larger volume and the higher degree of risk.</p></blockquote><p>The noises of disapproval from Germany over the European Central Bank's actions have been growing in recent weeks. Recently, Weidmann himself called for a return to more conventional monetary policy.</p><p>UPDATE: In the readers comments below, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/ratpack2233\">ratpack2233</a> points out that <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/comment-permalink/15125827\">Weidmann has intensified his attack</a> on the ECB. In particular, he is concerned that the ECB's payments system called Target2 has left the Bundesbank with claims worth more than €550bn against other eurozone members. Full story in <a href=\"http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/wirtschaftspolitik/f-a-z-gastbeitrag-bundesbank-geht-im-targetstreit-in-die-offensive-11682060.html\">FAZ</a>, but ratpack2233's done <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/comment-permalink/15125827\">a handy summary</a>.</p><!-- Block 9 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">10.01am:</span> European financial markets are in good spirits this morning, with the <strong>FTSE 100</strong> up 43 points at 5936, a rise of 0.75%. The French <strong>CAC</strong> and the German <strong>DAX</strong> are both up just over 1%.</p><p>Any relief over Greece may be only short-term. R<strong>ebecca O'Keeffe</strong>, head of investment at <strong>Interactive Investor</strong>, said traders are already talking about how long we will have to wait for the next crisis:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Before the ink is even dry on Greece's second bailout, the question that is being asked is how long it will take before Europe has to go into round three, and who the main player in round three will be? Current favourite is Spain, where the focus of attention has swiftly moved, and their deficit reduction plans.</p></blockquote><!-- Block 8 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">9.45am:</span> Britain's exports to non-EU countries posted a record increase in January, according to the latest UK trade figures, released at 9.30am.</p><p>Overall, the figures show that Britain's deficit with the rest of the world has increased, but by less than expected. The total balance of goods and services hit -£1.762bn in January, up from -£1.217bn in December.</p><p>As usual, a large deficit in exports vs imports of physical goods was partly countered by a large surplus in services. Here's the data for January:</p><p><strong>Goods balance</strong>         -£7.532bn (vs -£7.184bn in December)<br />    <strong>Exports</strong>             £26.063bn (vs £25.563bn in December) <br />    <strong>Imports</strong>  £33.595bn  (vs £32.747bn in December)     <br /><strong>Services balance</strong>       £5.786bn (vs 5.951bn in December)     </p><p><strong>Total trade balance</strong>   -£1.762bn  (vs -£1.217bn in December)</p><p>Economists reckon that the data is encouraging, showing that UK industry is coping quite well in the face of the eurocrisis. George Osborne should also be cheered. Philip Shaw of Investec said the figures were \"fairly encouraging\" for deficit reduction.</p><!-- Block 7 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">9.28am:</span> Has the EU opened a can of worms by agreeing that Spain shouldn't be forced to stick to its original deficit targets (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/13/eurozone-crisis-greek-deal-spain-austerity#block-2\">see 8.12am for details</a>)?</p><p><strong>Sony Kapoor</strong>, managing director of the Re-Define economic thinktank, argues that Spain is now the 'test case' for how Europe attempts to control the budgets of member states, in the brave new world of the <strong>Treaty on Stability, Co-ordination and Governance</strong> (the 'fiscal pact').</p><p><strong>Kapoor</strong> said we should:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Expect the battle about permissible levels of Spanish deficits to be replayed across a growing number of Euro area Member States.</p><p>Efforts to cut deficits too quickly in Spain could easily turn self-defeating particularly given the record levels of unemployment, the fragile state of the housing market and the weakness of the banking system.</p></blockquote><p><strong>Elisabeth Afseth</strong> of Investec said Mariano Rajoy had been given a 'telling off' for setting unilateral deficit targets last month (heck, he's only the prime minister), and also queried whether the fiscal compact had much teeth -- as many European countries failed to stick to the dusty old Stability and Growth Pact (France and Germany, for example).</p><p><strong>Afseth</strong> said:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>As all women know a compact is a concealer and foundation all in one (some would argue the fiscal compact is a better concealer than foundation). Very handy, but if it takes a bit of a knock there will be a lot of mess and you might as well just throw it out as it would be easier to put Humpty Dumpty together again.</p></blockquote><!-- Block 6 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">9.08am:</span> Andrew Tyrie, chairman of the Treasury Select Committee, argued last night that Greece should use the window of opportunity created by its new aid package to devise a way to quit the euro.</p><p>Tyrie told a dinner organised by the British Venture Capital and Private Equity Association that Greece will not be able to absorb the economic and political challenges it faces while still remaining within the currency union.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387297114'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Columnist/Columnists/2012/1/12/1326394733173/Andrew-Tyrie-005.jpg' alt='Andrew Tyrie' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Photograph: Felix Clay</figcaption></figure><p>The Daily Telegraph has <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/financialcrisis/9139702/Greece-should-exit-the-euro-says-Treasury-Select-Committee-chairman-Andrew-Tyrie.html\">more details</a>.</p><p>Tyrie generally appears to be one of the most financially astute MPs, so his comments will carry weight within Westminster. His comments on the IMF were also interesting -- agreeing that the Fund should be given more firepower, but should also take a tougher line with Europe.</p><!-- Block 5 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">8.55am:</span> As my colleague <strong>Julia Kollewe</strong> <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/13/greece-bailout-package-signed-off\">explains here</a>, the task of giving Europe's final, final approval to Greece will probably be made by junior offficials on Wednesday.</p><p>That's just a formality, now that the eurogroup ministers have given their approval.</p><!-- Block 4 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387297115'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2010/04/09/recap1.gif' alt='Live blog: recap' width='40' height='40' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">8.41am:</span> Quite a busy agenda today, with meetings continuing in Brussels, and various key players in the eurocrisis speaking - plus an interest rate decision in America.</p><p>Here's today's agenda:</p><p>• ECOFIN meeting in Brussels  - all day<br />• UK Trade data for January 9.30am<br />• Germany's ZEW economic sentiment survey - 10am GMT / 11am CET<br />• Jens Weidmann, Bundesbank president, holds press conference 10am GMT / 11am CET<br />• Mario Draghi give speech on \"challenges of competitiveness\", Paris  - 11.30am GMT <br />• France's Francois Baroin and Germany's Wolfgang Schäuble speak in Paris. 4.30pm GMT / 5.30pm CET<br />• UK Federal Reserve announces monetary policy decision - 8.15pm GMT / 2.15pm EST</p><!-- Block 3 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">8.29am:</span> Some early action in the credit ratings world – <strong>Moody's has slashed Cyprus's credit rating into Junk status, and blamed the Greek debt deal.</strong></p><p>Moody's cuts Cyprus's sovereign rating by one notch to 'Ba1' from 'Baa3', with a negative outlook. That means the island's debt is no longer seen as investment grade.</p><p>Moody's warned that the Cyprus government will have to inject fresh capital into its banks to cover losses incurred through Greece's debt swap. There is, it said, a \"very material risk\" that the private sector will fail to provide all the new funds itself.</p><p>It's another sign of the knock-on effects of the Greek deal. Cyprus's banks were highly exposed to Greek debt, relative to other banks, so are disproportionately hit by the haircut taken by creditors. Cyprus itself is also frozen out of the financial markets at present, and is relying on a loan from Russia.</p><!-- Block 2 --><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387297116'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2010/5/6/1273135489143/Live-blog---Spanish-flag-001.jpg' alt='Live blog - Spanish flag' width='60' height='40' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><span class=\"timestamp\">8.12am:</span> Depending how you look at it, the Eurogroup's decision on <strong>Spain</strong> last night can be seen either as a concession or an imposition.</p><p>Here's the bare facts. The EU now wants Spain to cut its deficit in 2012 to <strong>5.3% of GDP</strong> this year. That's less taxing than the previous target of <strong>4.4%</strong>, but harder than <strong>5.8% of GDP</strong> that the Madrid government set as its new target last month.</p><p>Jean-Claude Juncker, chair of the eurogroup, argued it was vital that Spain gets its deficit in 2013 down to 3% of GDP by making tough decisions this year. He said:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>It will be the responsibility of the Spanish authorities to choose the initiatives that will have to be taken in order to bring down the budgetary deficit in 2012, what is most important is what is the target for 2013.</p><p>What is less important, but nevertheless important, are the avenues chosen in 2012.</p></blockquote><p>Spain's deficit is a key issue because the country came nowhere close to hitting its targets in 2011. Last year's deficit came in at 8.5%, far above the 6.0% goal. That was mainly because its regional governments failed to achieve their own targets.</p><p>Juncker appeared to rule out penalising Spain for last year's performance, indicating that was consigned to history. As he put it:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The figure announced previously by the Spanish government... is dead.</p></blockquote><!-- Block 1 --><p><span class=\"timestamp\">8.05am:</span> Good morning, and welcome to our rolling coverage of <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/12/eurozone-crisis-live-new-greek-bonds-start-trading\">the eurozone debt crisis</a>.</p><p>Overnight, European finance ministers finallly agreed that Greece's €130bn (£109bn) rescue package should proceed. Although the official stamp of approval won't come until tomorrow, this means that the Eurogroup have - at last - accepted that Greece has done everything demanded of it.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/mar/12/greek-debt-eurozone-bonds-talks\">The talks in Brussels</a> also saw Spain move centre-stage. European leaders insisted on tougher cutbacks than prime minister Mariano Rajoy recently announced, but also abandoned their old deficit targets.</p><p>Is the focus of the crisis moving away from Athens, and over to Madrid?</p><p>As usual, we'll be tracking all the latest developments and reactions. Let us know what you think too...</p>","headline":"Eurozo