ian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/18/eurozone-crisis-greece-talks-cuts#block-5006d9c158f90c7116d8352a\">Analyst: IMF is right</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/18/eurozone-crisis-greece-talks-cuts#block-5006dc9bc0e37695247b8ecb\">Greece has not found €11.7bn savings, yet...</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/18/eurozone-crisis-greece-talks-cuts#block-500685c5c0e339808183c0b5\">Germany sells debt at negative yields</a>","hasStoryPackage":"true","lastModified":"2012-09-03T14:38:36.854+01:00","firstPublicationDate":"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00","body":"<div id=\"block-5006de82c0e37695247b8ecd\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><em><strong>And that's the end of the live-blog for the day. Thanks all, and goodnight.....</strong></em><br></p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006dc9bc0e37695247b8ecb\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>News in from Greece where our correspondent <strong>Helena Smith</strong> confirms that the thriller over the country finding €11.5 bn in savings as prescribed by international creditors continues apace.</p><p>Helena writes: </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Greek finance ministry officials say discussions on how Athens will meet the magic target of €11.5bn in cuts will continue “right up until the troika returns next week.” Yiannis Stournaras, the finance minister, will meet with visiting representatives from the EU, ECB and IMF next Thursday. </p><p>“Up until the moment Stournaras meets the troika talks will continue on how the money will be found,” a senior aide to the minister confided. “Today, agreement was made on the general direction not the details [of the cuts],” he said adding that prime minister Antonis Samaras and his two junior party leaders had reached consensus on €8.1bn in savings – almost €4bn short of what Greece’s creditors want to see. </p><p>  Emerging from the meeting the media friendly Stournaras insisted that “we still don’t have concrete measures.” He left open the prospect of across the board cuts that might affect pensions and wages - a red rag for Greeks who after more than two years of punishing belt-tightenting have seen their disposable incomes drop by 40%.  “The €11.5bn is not an issue [to be solved] tomorrow. A conversation with the troika will take place next week. They must also agree so I am not ready today to say any more about it,” said Stournaras. “I don’t want to commit to anything … today we spoke generally. We will continue the conversation.”  The minister added that the €3bn budget black hole that has emerged this year would definitely be plugged and that by next week €11.5bn would be found.  But the vagueness of statements made after the meeting has left plenty of room for anti-bailout stalwarts to hit back. Within minutes after today’s talks, Alexis Tsipras, firebrand leader of the far left Syriza party, shot back saying the three-party coalition was “lying” about its true intent which was to implement a “catastrophic plan” of yet more austerity measures.  </p><p>“The government is executing orders from the troika and is not serving the public interest,” he said, denouncing the EU, ECB and IMF officials as “a failed committee of employees” who he would refuse to meet. The leader called on the government to request “an emergency meeting of European leaders to discuss a new strategic plan for the Greek case.” </p></blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006da8158f90c7116d8352b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Europe's financial markets have just closed, with the major markets finishing higher. Here's a summary:</p><p><strong>FTSE 100:</strong> up 56 points at 5685, + 1.0%<br><strong>German DAC:</strong> up 100 points at 6678, + 1.53%<br><strong>French CAC</strong>: up 52 points at 3229, + 1.67%<br><strong>Spanish IBEX: </strong>up 33 points at 6591, + 0.5%<br><strong>Italian FTSE MIB:</strong> up 57 points at 13594, + 0.43% </p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006d9c158f90c7116d8352a\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Nicholas Spiro of Spiro Sovereign Strategy has welcomed the IMF's new report on the eurozone (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/18/eurozone-crisis-greece-talks-cuts#block-5006ba48c0e37695247b8eb8\">see 14.29pm</a>), calling it a \"nuts-and-bolts manual for crisis management\". </p><p>He calls the report a cri de coeur (or cry from the heart) to Germany and the ECB, to act now to restore confidence, saying:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The tone of the report is alarmist, and intentionally so. For the IMF, the eurozone is now in the last chance saloon. Time is of the essence. <br></p></blockquote><p>The report is online at the IMF's website, called: <a href=\"http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/survey/so/2012/INT071812A.htm\">IMF Calls on Eurozone to Take Determined Action in Response to Crisis.</a></p><p>Spiro continues:<br><a href=\"http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/survey/so/2012/INT071812A.htm\"> </a></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Although a comprehensive report, its message is clear: the causes and symptoms of the eurozone crisis have yet to be meaningfully addressed and require credible short and longer-term measures to sever the links between banks and sovereigns and mitigate the effects of fiscal austerity. Half-rescues are not going to work and the risks of the crisis escalating further are significant. </p><p> The IMF believes the eurozone is currently facing the worst of both worlds: it is sufficiently integrated for contagion to spread like wildfire but institutionally and politically unprepared to deal with its consequences. <br></p></blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006d57ac0e37695247b8eca\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Asked about Europe's debt crisis, Ben Bernanke warns:<br></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>I don’t think they’re close to finding a long-term solution.</p></blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006d17ac0e37695247b8ec9\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Congressman <strong>Michael Capuano</strong>, from Massachusetts, has raised a question about Libor during Ben Bernanke's testimony to the House Financial Services Committee. </p><p>If it transpires that America's biggest banks had \"intentionally lied\" to interfere with the inter-bank lending rates, should those responsible be brought to justice, be it civil or criminal charges?<br></p><p>Unsurprisingly, <strong>Ben Bernanke</strong> thinks they should, pointing out that there is \"no shortage of investigations\" into the scandal.<br></p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006cb2e58f90c7116d83527\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Hmmm. Committee chairman Spencer Bachus just warned that America is heading towards a \"physical cliff\" next year (when the US is hit by tax rises and spending cuts equal to 5% of GDP).</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-886b69b4-d31d-4bd6-9873-08a7f215adda\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/7/18/1342622888448/-460.jpeg\" alt=\"Spencer Bachus, Republican congressman for Alabama.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Spencer Bachus, Republican congressman for Alabama.</figcaption> </figure>  <p>A physical cliff sounds scarier than a fiscal one – so anything that concentrates minds in Washington should be applauded. I guess....</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/HughesNews/status/225600155133550593\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Yep RT @<a href=\"https://twitter.com/Neil_Irwin\">Neil_Irwin</a>: Did Spencer Bachus just call it the 'physical cliff\"?</p>&mdash; Megan Hughes (@HughesNews) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/HughesNews/status/225600155133550593\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-18T14:37:23+00:00\">July 18, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006c83fc0e37695247b8ec5\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Ben Bernanke is now reading his testimony to the House Financial Services Committee. It is IDENTICAL to the speech he read out yesterday to the Senate Committee on Banking, Housing, and Urban Affairs. <a href=\"http://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/testimony/bernanke20120717a.htm\">The text is here</a>.<br></p><p>Given the crisis in the global economy, this may not be the best use of Bernanke's time.</p><p>Binyamin Appelbau of the The New York Times agrees:</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/BCAppelbaum/status/225596731893620738\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>And now the second most powerful man in the world will waste 10 minutes repeating exactly what he said yesterday. Why?</p>&mdash; Binyamin Appelbaum (@BCAppelbaum) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/BCAppelbaum/status/225596731893620738\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-18T14:23:46+00:00\">July 18, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006c601c0e37695247b8ec4\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>If you'd like to watch Ben Bernanke's session at the House Financial Services Committee, <a href=\"http://www.c-span.org/Events/Fed-Chairman-Returns-to-Capitol-Hill-for-Monetary-Policy-Report/10737432397-1/\">it is being streamed live here</a>.</p><p>Nothing serious to report yet – some congressmen have been delivering statements before Bernanke gets down to business. </p><p><strong>Spencer Bachus</strong>, chairman of the committee, warned that the chairman of the Federal Reserve could not be expected to save the economy when politicians are determined to \"send the economy over the fiscal cliff\". </p><p><strong>And republican Ron Paul</strong> has talked about how the collapse of the Bretton Woods system 40 years led to an unsustainable credit boom, huge debts in some countries, the \"fiat dollar\", and a situation where policymakers are blundering by increasing spending and borrowing.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006c3a8c0e37695247b8ec2\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Ben Bernanke is testifying in Washington for the second day running. <br></p><p>The head of the US Federal Reserve just sat down in front of the House Financial Services Committee, to continue his semi-annual testimony.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-f9d0ba08-179d-480a-82ec-e3b7dce1591b\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/7/18/1342620476210/-460.jpeg\" alt=\"Ben Bernanke of the Federal Reserve\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Ben Bernanke of the Federal Reserve. Photo: C-Span</figcaption> </figure>  <p>Not sure how much we can expect to learn, given that yesterday Bernanke romped through the main issues – QE3 (not yet), the fiscal cliff (bad!), the Libor scandal (shocking!) and the eurozone (threatening the world economy). But we'll watch and see....</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006bd49c0e37695247b8ebe\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">   <p>The full statement issued by the IMF on the state of the eurozone (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/18/eurozone-crisis-greece-talks-cuts#block-5006ba48c0e37695247b8eb8\">see 14.29</a>) is now online here.</p><p>It includes this blunt warning:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The euro area crisis has intensified. Adverse links between banks, sovereigns, and the real economy have deepened, driving sovereign borrowing costs and risk premiums to record levels. Investors are withholding funding from member states most in need, moving capital \"north\" and abroad to perceived safer assets. This has contributed to divergences in liquidity conditions and lending rates within the euro area, adding to already-severe pressures on many bank and sovereign balance sheets and raising questions about the viability of the monetary union itself.</p><p> Economic activity has weakened and is likely to remain subdued, particularly in the hard-hit periphery countries.</p></blockquote>  </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006ba48c0e37695247b8eb8\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">IMF calls on ECB to act</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">   <p>The International Monetary Fund is pleading with the European Central Bank to do more to fix the eurozone crisis.</p><p>In a report released at 2pm, the IMF said the ECB could, and should, do more to prevent the euro unravelling, arguing:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The ECB can provide further defences against an escalation of the crisis.</p></blockquote><p>Its recommendations included</p><p><strong> • considering further interest rate cuts<br></strong></p><p><strong>• A \"sizeable\" quantitative easing package, to stimulate the eurozone economy</strong></p><p><strong>• giving the ECB full 'lender of last resort' powers</strong></p><p><strong>• restarting its Securities Markets Progamme (to buy up peripheral sovereign debt)</strong></p><p>Suggestions 2, 3 and 4 are unlikely to be welcomed by stronger members of the eurozone (think Germany, Austria, Finland...) who could also fear that lower interest rates would drive inflation up.<br></p><p>The IMF, though (which expects the eurozone to contract by 0.3% this year) is again insisting that the ECB must do more:<br></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>These could include policies to support demand in the short run and fend off downside risks to inflation, as well as measures to ensure that monetary transmission, currently impaired by financial stress in some countries.</p></blockquote><p>There are problems with the IMF's suggestions, though. QE would probably drag down the yields on safer bonds (awkward, when some are in negative territory already), while Germany is wedded to the idea that closer fiscal union needs to be arranged <strong>before</strong> the ECB is granted more powers.<br></p>  </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006b4a158f9673bbacb820e\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Some photos from today's negotiations in Athens have arrived. Here, Evangelos Venizelos, left, and Fotis Kouvelis are shown leaving the meeting.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-922c83e9-ded4-4ec0-bd8a-25b033c214c1\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/7/18/1342616320859/f575fbb0-854a-42be-87e3-dd3c3ba66f95-460.jpeg\" alt=\"Evangelos Venizelos and Fotis Kouvelis in Athens, 18 July 2012.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>And another thing! Photo credit: Thanassis Stavrakis/AP</figcaption> </figure>  <p>Meanwhile, the claim that there will be no additional spending cuts has been rejected by opposition leader Alexis Tsipras, who accused the leaders of lying (Greek journalist <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EfiEfthimiou\">Efthimia Efthimiou</a> reports)  </p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/EfiEfthimiou/status/225576204185509888\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/search/%2523Greece2012\">#Greece2012</a> Tsipras (Syriza): Govt is lying when says that there will not be new measures. There will be new measures</p>&mdash; Efthimia Efthimiou (@EfiEfthimiou) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EfiEfthimiou/status/225576204185509888\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-18T13:02:12+00:00\">July 18, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/EfiEfthimiou/status/225576673268076545\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/search/%2523Greece2012\">#Greece2012</a> Tsipras: Govt is doing what Troika wants and doesnt protect people</p>&mdash; Efthimia Efthimiou (@EfiEfthimiou) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EfiEfthimiou/status/225576673268076545\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-18T13:04:04+00:00\">July 18, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006b12cc0e339808183c0c4\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Worrying signs in the bond markets, where Spanish 10-year yields have climbed back to 6.94%</strong>. That's a rise of 11 basis points (ie, from 6.83% overnight).</p> <p>The trigger appears to be <a href=\"http://www.ifamagazine.com/news/spain-is-ultimately-liable-for-bank-bailout-says-schauble/13685/\">comments from Germany's finance minister, Wolfgang Sch&auml;uble, about how Spain remains ultimately liable for the bailout of its banking sector</a>.</p> <p>This comes as the yield on safer government debt drops to new lows (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/18/eurozone-crisis-greece-talks-cuts#block-500685c5c0e339808183c0b5\">as covered at 10.45</a>). So investors appear to be losing faith in Spain again (while Italian 10-year yields are only slightly higher, at 6.06%).</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.twitter.com/sonykapoor\"><strong>Sony Kapoor</strong></a> has dubbed this trend the \"<strong><em>eurozone dumbbell trap</em></strong>\" &ndash; the idea being that euro countries will be pushed further apart into two different groups [one with low borrowing costs and relatively low unemployment and decent economic growth, and the other struggling to borrow, with austerity measures driving people out of work, and causing a recession].</p> <p>So the 'core' of the eurozone feels less urgency to fix the crisis, while the 'periphery' suffers so much damage that exit from the single currency becomes more likely. <a href=\"http://www.businessinsider.com/diverging-borrowing-costs-are-killing-progress-in-europe-2012-7?utm_source=twbutton&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_campaign=moneygame\">There's a good article on this issue on Business Insider today</a>.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006a6b158f9673bbacb820d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>We can safely say that Greek leaders have not reached a final agreement over the €11.7bn spending cuts needed. <a href=\"http://in.reuters.com/article/2012/07/18/greece-talks-idINA8E8HL00A20120718\">They have agreed to hold another meeting next week</a> to discuss the issue again.<br></p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006a0ecc0e339808183c0c1\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>A bit more detail from Athens – a finance ministry official has said that the leaders have now agreed €8.1bn of new measures, against the target of €11.7bn.</p><p>The official added that all parties remain commited to \"asset sales\" (that's via Blooomberg).</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-50069a1058f9673bbacb8208\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>There are reports from Athens that Greek leaders have agreed not to impose new budget measures this year, and will start work on the 2013 budget this autumn</strong>.<br></p><p>It's a confusing picture, but here goes:<br></p><p>Pasok leader Evangelos Venizelos and finance minister Yiannis Stournaras have been briefing the media following the conclusion of talks with prime minister Samaras.</p><p>Stournaras declines to go into full detail about what was actually agreed, saying that \"There is some road ahead of us.\" <br></p><p>Venizelos said the meeting with coalition leaders was \"useful and essential\". The Pasok chief said it was essential that Greece proves its credibility to the international community by pushing on with measures to restructure its economy.</p><p>Venizelos reiterated that Greece's fiscal adjustment program must be extended (presumably by another two years, as he's previously suggested?).</p><p>Democratic Left's Fotis Kouvelis also released a statement. He said the leaders had agreed to draw up a detailed plan that would allow Greece to ask for its fiscal adjustment plan to be renegotiated and extended.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-50069050c0e339808183c0bb\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Breaking news</strong> – the meeting in Athens has just broken up, after more than three hours.</p><p>There are reports that Antonis Samaras, Evangelos Venizelos and Fotis Kouvelis have reached \"an agreement in principle\" over the €11.7bn of austerity measures demanded by Greece's lenders.<br></p><p>(Helena's post at 11.14 has full details of the talks).</p><p>A statement should be released soon, according to the ever-clued-up <strong>Diane Shugart</strong> in Athens, a Greek citizen tracking the crisis.<br></p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/dianalizia/status/225538771523862528\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>finmin stournaras said pm+2 agreed on where cuts should come from; details in govt spokesman venizelos, kouvelis statements soon</p>&mdash; Diane Shugart (@dianalizia) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/dianalizia/status/225538771523862528\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-18T10:33:28+00:00\">July 18, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-50068c9858f9673bbacb8205\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">Latest news from Athens talks</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p> Over to Greece where our correspondent <strong>Helena Smith</strong> has the latest on today’s critical meeting in Athens, where leaders are trying to agree ways to come up with €11.7bn in spending cuts.</p><p><strong>Helena</strong> writes: </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Insiders say the Greek finance minister Yiannis Stournaras has spent the best part of the talks, so far, presenting a list of proposed cuts that could make up the estimated €4.5bn still missing when the meeting began between prime minister Antonis Samaras and the leaders of his two junior coalition partners. </p><p>Acutely aware of the boiling cauldron that Greece has become after almost three years of biting austerity policies, Samaras wants to avoid measures that would affect wages and pensions at all costs. But across the board cuts and more tax increases may ultimately be unavoidable, government officials say. </p><p>The state-run news channel ERT quoted a senior finance ministry official this morning as saying “we are trying to avoid it but cannot rule it out. There are voices in the Euro group (of eurozone finance ministers) calling for addition measures, which we are trying to avoid by pointing to the greater-than-expected recession.” Other financial ministry sources said today that the leaders may well agree on a “general outline” of cuts without getting into the detail of what, exactly, they might be. </p></blockquote>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-84bd7e49-69da-4d94-9c3e-4e7623481a43\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2012/6/26/1340714516871/Yannis-Stournaras-Greeces-008.jpg\" alt=\"Yannis Stournaras, Greece's new finance minister\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Yannis Stournaras, Greece's new finance minister. Photograph: Giannis Panagopoulos/AP</figcaption> </figure>  <p><strong>Stournaras</strong> is expected to present “two scenarios” listing cuts worth €11.7bn – a precondition of Greece’s latest €130bn rescue package – when he meets visiting inspectors from Greece’s “troika” of creditors at the EU, ECB and IMF, next Thursday. </p><p><strong>Helena</strong> continues:<br></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The monitors are due to return to Athens on 24 or 15 July to put the final touches to a progress report on which the debt-stricken country’s next €31.5bn tranche of aid will depend. Under the first scenario favoured by lenders, the cuts will extend over a two-year period starting in 2013. Under the second, favoured by Greece, they will stretch out over a four-year period beginning next year. “It is vital that we show willing and so are preparing two sets of proposals. We realise that international patience is running out,” said one source. </p><p>Stournaras, like all three party leaders, is keen to renegotiate Greece’s latest bailout, firmly believing that after three years of implementation the programme shows little sign of yanking the country out of its economic death spiral. But the Oxford-educated economist says it is crucial that Athens claws back some of its credibility first by keeping to the pledges it made when it signed up to the international rescue package in March. “Once we have shown we are serious we will begin negotiating,” one insider said. </p><p>At the very least Athens wants to prolong the time period over which it will meet deficit reducing targets with many in the government seeing the extension “as a given”. Auditors, however, say prolongation alone is a “huge ask” and may not happen. Greek officials who participated in the fraught negotiations that ultimately sealed the latest rescue package privately admit that the government could be setting itself “and the Greek people” up for huge disappointment. “Our creditors are in no mood to renegotiate,” said a senior official. “To agree on this package in the first place took long enough. All this talk is very dangerous … All of them [party leaders in the government] are playing with fire.” <br></p></blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006895358f9673bbacb8204\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Here's some reaction to Germany's record-breaking bond auction (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/18/eurozone-crisis-greece-talks-cuts#block-500685c5c0e339808183c0b5\">see 10.45</a>).</p><p>Bond strategist <strong>Nick Stamenkovic</strong> said the popularity of Germany debt was partly due to last week's interest rate cut from the ECB.</p><p><strong>Stamenkovic</strong> added:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>With the economic picture looking so poor at the moment, yields could remain negative at the short end [ie, for lower maturity bonds] for some time to come, and could go even deeper into negative territory.</p></blockquote><p><strong>Sony Kapoor</strong> of the <strong>Re-Define</strong> thinktank is concerned by the auction, saying politicians should not take low yields as proof they are handling the crisis well.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/SonyKapoor/status/225528927584661504\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Dear <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search/%2523EU\">#EU</a> leaders, the falling yields r not a sign of success 4 ur non-strategy but a symptom of its deep failure, a sign of desperation!</p>&mdash; Sony Kapoor (@SonyKapoor) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/SonyKapoor/status/225528927584661504\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-18T09:54:21+00:00\">July 18, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500685c5c0e339808183c0b5\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Crumbs! Germany has just sold more than €4bn of two-year debt at negative yields.</strong></p><p>This is the first time ever that investors have paid more than the face value of the debt in this kind of German auction, and is another sign of the dash for safety.</p><p><strong>The Bundesbank sold €4.173 of two-year bonds, or Schatz, at an average yield of 0.06%</strong> (in general terms, yield is the rate of return on the bond).</p><p>Ahead of the auction, UK, French and Austrian government bonds had strengthened to their highest ever prices, pushing down the yields to record lows.</p><p><strong>Linda Yueh</strong> of <strong>Bloomberg</strong> helpfully tweeted the details:</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/lindayueh/status/225519500630568960\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Record lows: France 10 year bond yield drops to 2.068%, Austria 10 year bond yield drops to 1.86%</p>&mdash; Linda Yueh (@lindayueh) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/lindayueh/status/225519500630568960\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-18T09:16:53+00:00\">July 18, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/lindayueh/status/225519929414254594\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>More record lows: UK 2 year gilt yield falls to 0.168%, 5 year too at 0.5%, France 5 year bond yield drops to 0.763%</p>&mdash; Linda Yueh (@lindayueh) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/lindayueh/status/225519929414254594\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-18T09:18:35+00:00\">July 18, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500682b258f9673bbacb8201\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">Bank of England minutes show split on QE</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>The Bank of England fears that the escalating eurozone crisis could destabilise the global banking sector, and drive the UK deeper into recession.<br></p><p>The minutes of its latest meeting, two weeks ago, showed that the Bank's monetary policy committee is deeply worried about the situation in the euro – which was instrumental in its decision to launch a third bout of quantitative easing, worth £50bn, this month.<br></p><p>The MPC met just a few days after the last EU summit, when the financial markets were still cheering the progress made on bank regulation, and aid for Spain.</p><p>The Bank, though, was not convinced. Here's the key line from today's minutes: </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Notwithstanding the initial positive market reaction to the political developments within the euro area, very substantial risks there remained.</p><p>These could, if they crystallised, have a considerable impact on economic activity in the United Kingdom and the stability <br>of the global banking system. <br></p><p>There were increasing signs that the threat of a disorderly resolution of the financial tensions in the euro area was affecting growth at home. Information during the month suggested that export prospects had weakened, which would further impede the UK economy’s rebalancing away from domestic demand towards net exports. </p></blockquote>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-b293bfdb-edcd-4810-af5c-6e4c69f3f2f2\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/7/18/1342604066934/8b0ed485-6eff-41a2-8609-4d67e906a419-460.jpeg\" alt=\"Bank of England policymaker Ben Broadbent \" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Ben Broadbent opposed the increase in QE, but was outgunned by other members of the MPC. Eddie Keogh/Reuters</figcaption> </figure>   <p>The minutes also showed that two members of the MPC – chief economist <strong>Spencer Dale</strong>, and external member <strong>Ben Broadbent</strong> (formerly of Goldmadn Sachs) – voted against the QE boost. They wanted to see how the Bank's new lending scheme worked first.</p>  </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-50067b0c58f9673bbacb81ff\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Economist <strong>Howard Archer</strong> of <strong>IHS Global Insigh</strong>t says that the drop in UK unemployment (to 8.1%) shows the UK labour market is showing \"impressive resiliance\", given the UK economy continued to shrink during the last three months.</p><p>One factor is that wages are being pegged back, meaning real-term pay cuts for millions of people whose salaries are not keeping up with inflation. <br></p><p><strong>Today's data showed average earnings rose by 1.5% year-on-year in May - inflation rose by 2.8% that month.<br></strong></p><p><strong> </strong>Another factor is a rise in part-time work, and the number of self-employed people.<br></p><p>Archer adds that the long-term jobs outlook for the UK looks \"problematic\".</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006776a58f9673bbacb81fd\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>The news that the UK unemployment rate has dipped to 8.1% (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/18/eurozone-crisis-greece-talks-cuts#block-5006756cc0e339808183c0b2\">see last post</a>) has been welcomed by the UK Treasury, with a spokesman pointing out that it is better than the 8.2% rate in America.</p><p>I'm reluctant to use the phrase 'good news' where any jobless data is involved - but there was a glimmer of hope in the youth unemployment stats, where the rate dipped to 21.9%, from 22.1%.</p><p>In the City, <strong>Jeremy Cook</strong> of <strong>WorldFirst</strong> warned that the jobless rate could rise in the autumn once the boost from the Olympics has finished, especially given the weak UK economy<br></p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/World_First/status/225509089906663424\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Dip in unemployment down to short-term temp jobs, unlikely to last post Olympics and through continued H2 slowdown</p>&mdash; World First (@World_First) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/World_First/status/225509089906663424\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-18T08:35:31+00:00\">July 18, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5006756cc0e339808183c0b2\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">UK UNEMPLOYMENT DATA RELEASED</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>The UK unemployment rate has fallen, as the London Olympics helped to create extra jobs.</p><p>The latest jobless data, just released, showed that the number of people out of work in the three months to May fell by 65,000, to 2.584m.</p><p><strong>That brings the unemployment rate down to 8.1%.</strong></p><p>The Office for National Statistics said there was \"some positive labour market impact\" from the Olympics.<br></p><p>But the ONS also reported that the number of people claiming unemployment benefit in June actually rose by 6,100 (more than economists had expected). That pushed the claimant count up to 1.6042m, but left the the rate unchanged at 4.9%.<br></p><p>Employment rose by 181,000 in the three months to May, taking the total number of people in work to 29.354m.<br><em><strong></strong></em></p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-bdccb533-5c83-429a-ba68-b762a25184b1\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/7/18/1342603008061/-460.jpeg\" alt=\"UK employment rate (aged 16-64) to May 2012, seasonally adjusted\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>This graph shows how the UK employment rate (aged 16-64) has risen in recent months, despite the recession.</figcaption> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500672ecc0e339808183c0b0\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-d058afb0-a20d-49f3-881c-f41748db41da\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/7/18/1342602123616/73f7111e-9cae-4582-89d4-c888dd8c2af4-460.jpeg\" alt=\"Anti-austerity protests in Madrid. \" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>A civil servant shouts slogans during a protest yesterday against austerity measures in front of the Treasury and Public Administration Ministry in Madrid. The poster reads: \"This is a robbery\". Juan Medina/Reuters</figcaption> </figure>  <p>Three interesting pieces of economic news from Spain have been released this morning, showing how its economy is worsening.</p><p>1) The Bank of Spain reported a rise in the ratio of bad loans on bank balance sheets, up to 8.95% in May from 8.72% in April. The total of non-performing debt is now €155.8bn.<br></p><p>2) The amount of money stored as deposits at Spanish banks fell by 5.75%, year-on-year, in May.</p><p>3) Spanish house prices fell 8.3% in the second quarter of 2012, compared with the previous year.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-50066ce958f9673bbacb81fb\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>A \"Perfect Storm\" will sweep through the world economy next year, with the eurocrisis escalating as the world economy judders to a halt.</p><p>That's the prediction from economist <strong>Nouriel Roubini</strong>, living up to his reputation as Dr Doom.<br></p><p><strong>Roubini</strong> believes five events will strike next year, driving the financial crisis to new depths. They are: a worsening of Europe's debt crisis; the US 'fiscal cliff'; a Chinese 'hard landing'; a slowdown across the emerging markets; and war with Iran.</p><p>As <strong>Roubini</strong> put it to Reuters:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Next year is the time when the can becomes too big to kick down (the road)... then we have a global perfect storm.</p></blockquote><p>Roubini's made this kind of prediction before, but it does seem to be coming true.</p><p>For example, yesterday <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/17/eurozone-crisis-mervyn-king-libor\">Ben Bernanke warned senators</a> that the US will be driven into recession by the tax rises and spending cuts arriving in 2013; while <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/jul/13/china-economic-growth-slows-gdp\">data released last Friday</a> showed that China's GDP growth is slowing.<br></p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500665b158f9673bbacb81f9\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Hanging over today's talks in Athens is the threat that the Troika might withhold the next tranche of loans that are scheduled to be handed to Greece in September.</p><p>Troika inspectors are due back in Greece on 24 July, to inspect the country's progress. So far, eurozone officials have pushed back against Antonis Samaras's proposal that the programme is extended by two years.</p><p>So, if his ministers can't agree the savings, Samaras may have to do the dirty work for them. </p><p>In Athens, <strong>Diane Shugart</strong> isn't optimistic about this morning's meeting (which will also be attended by finance minister Stournaras)</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/dianalizia/status/225461559986630656\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>samaras, venizelos, and kouvelis face political decision on what cuts to make to meet €11bn goal. expect them to make the wrong decisions</p>&mdash; Diane Shugart (@dianalizia) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/dianalizia/status/225461559986630656\" data-datetime=\"2012-07-18T05:26:39+00:00\">July 18, 2012</a></blockquote> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-500662bb58f9673bbacb81f8\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Greek PM Antonis Samaras called this morning's meeting after his ministers failed to find the €11.7bn of cuts demanded by the Troika.<br><br>At the last estimate, under €6b of savings had been agreed for 2013 and 2014. <br><br>Finance minister Yannis Stournaras has been holding talks with other ministers over the last two days, but some members of the government have proved reluctant to propose large savings.<br><br>Evangelos Venezelos has admitted that Athens may not be able to make such hefty savings, warning last night that:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>It is very difficult, almost impossible, for anyone to put cuts together worth €11.5bn in 2013 and 2014...<br></p></blockquote><blockquote>That difficulty has always been there, but the (situation) has deteriorated because the predictions for the recession in 2012.<br></blockquote><p>Not an encouraging start to today's meeting... Venizelos makes an important point, though – Greece's economy (along with much of the eurozone) has performed worse than expected recently, making it even harder to hit targets agreed a few months ago.<br></p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-50065fcb58f9673bbacb81f7\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2012-09-03T14:38:36.879+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Good morning, and welcome to <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/debt-crisis\">our rolling coverage of Europe's financial crisis</a>, and other breaking news from across the global economy.</p><p>There are important developments in Greece today, as the Athens government struggles to find more than €11bn of new austerity measures.<br></p><p>Prime minister <strong>Antonis Samaras</strong> is holding talks with the leaders of the junior parties in his coalition – <strong>Evangelos Venizelos</strong> of Pasok, and <strong>Fotis Kouvelis</strong> of Democratic Left – in an attempt to break the deadlock.<br></p><p>The meeting was scheduled to start at <strong>10am local time (8am BST)</strong>, so we'll be watching for developments. Greece needs to agree the cuts, to satisfy its Troika of creditors.</p><p>Elsewhere, it's a lively morning for UK economic data. The latest unemployment figures will be released at 9.30am BST, along with the minutes of the Bank of England's last meeting (when it voted to throw another £50bn of quantitative easing at the ailing British economy).</p><p>And in America, <strong>Ben Bernanke</strong> is heading back to Capitol Hill this afternoon for a second day of testimony to US politicians.<br></p> </div>   </div>","headline":"Eurozone crisis live: IMF issues euro warning as Greece struggles to make cuts - as it happened","trailText":"<p>Greek PM Antonis Samaras's government still needs to agree more than €3bn of spending cuts; IMF calls on the ECB to do more to save the eurozone<br /></p>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/10/26/1319655496800/eurozone-crisis-003.jpg","wordcount":"4349","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"393251101","allowUgc":"false","internalComposerCode":"524ecbcbe4b0b103eb47f536","isPremoderated":"false