d is it going to get? As chair of the Office for Budget Responsibility, Robert Chote is the government's independent forecaster-in-chief and the man responsible for checking that George Osborne's budget figures add up. In a wide-ranging interview, Chote discussed the eurozone crisis and much else. Here are the main points.</p><p></p><p><strong>• Chote said Greece leaving the euro could plunge Britain into a recession as bad as the last one, causing long-term damage to the economy.</strong> He stressed the difficulties of forecasting the economic consequences of a Greek exit, but acknowledged there was a danger \"not just that the economy weakens and then strengthens again – ie, it goes into a hole and comes out – but that you go down and you never quite get back up to where you started\".</p><p></p><p><strong>• He said there was no evidence to show that cutting the 50p top rate of tax would promote growth.</strong> \"We didn't feel that there was a strong enough evidence base to say our long-term or medium-term view of the economy is now more optimistic than it was beforehand as a result of that measure,\" he said.</p><p></p><p><strong>• He said current spending on public sector pensions was sustainable in the long-term. </strong>The public finances as a whole would come under pressure in years to come, but the current pension regime was \"not where the problem is coming from\", he said.</p><p></p><p><strong>• He claimed that the OBR was better at producing reliable forecasts than the Treasury used to be.</strong> \"On public sector net borrowing … our errors are by and large smaller than the average errors were under the old regime [when the Treasury was in charge of producing forecasts for the government],\" he said, producing figures showing that seven out of nine of the OBR's borrowing forecasts to date had been shown to be more accurate than Treasury ones were. He also produced figures showing that the OBR's growth forecasts were more reliable than average Treasury ones. Asked to explain why the OBR got it so wrong when it predicted reasonable growth in 2011 and 2012, he said higher-than-expected inflation, particularly from oil prices and food prices, was mainly to blame.</p><p></p><p><strong>• He said the OBR should eventually be allowed to cost opposition policies. </strong>Under current legislation, it is banned from doing this. \"Having independent rigorous analysis of all the political parties' policies is a good thing for them, it's a good thing for public debate, it's a good thing for democracy,\" he said. He also suggested that the current arrangement, which will allow Osborne to go into the election saying his plans have been approved by the OBR while Ed Balls won't be able to make the same claim, was potentially unfair.</p><p></p><p>The Office for Budget Responsibility, which was set up by Osborne after the election, sounds rather grand. But actually Chote's team is only about 20-strong and they operate from a rather poky office on Victoria Street. There are two-bit PR companies with larger headcounts and plusher premises.</p><p>Chote used to run the Institute for Fiscal Studies (employing about 50 people), and helped to establish it as the thinktank most trusted to impartially dissect government and opposition fiscal policies. \"The fact that we looked at every party's plans, and normally said rude things about all of them, contributed to people's sense of our independence and our evenhandedness,\" he said. At the OBR he's more constrained because he's not allowed to comment on opposition policies, and whether they would be better than Osborne's. But in our interview he still managed to say at least two things likely to annoy Osborne (on the 50p top rate of tax, and public sector pensions), and one that will go down badly with Balls (on the reason for growth being much lower than expected). We spoke on Wednesday afternoon. Here's how it went.</p><p></p><h2>Eurozone crisis</h2><p></p><p><strong>Q: At his </strong><a href=\"http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/publications/Documents/inflationreport/irspnote160512.pdf\" title=\"\"><strong>press conference on Wednesday morning (pdf)</strong></a><strong>, Sir Mervyn King, the governor of the Bank of England, seemed to be saying – and I paraphrase – that it was so difficult trying to work out the impact of Greece leaving the eurozone that there was no point even trying. The OBR's position is different, because in your last </strong><a href=\"http://budgetresponsibility.independent.gov.uk/pubs/March-2012-EFO1.pdf\" title=\"\"><strong>economic and fiscal outlook (pdf)</strong></a><strong>, you did try to quantify it. Can you summarise what would happen?</strong></p><p>A: Fundamentally the governor is right, and we've taken a similar approach in most of the recent forecasts that we've done. If you think about the bad outcome for the eurozone, there are so many different ways in which that could unfold that picking any one and working out the consequences of that for the economy and the public finances, and saying that that is representative of the bad outcome, isn't particularly helpful. There's an awful lot of uncertainty. For example, if Greece were to come out, does that make people more confident about the stability and cohesion of what is left? Or are people more nervous because they fear there will be contagion?</p><p>That said, you can say hopefully useful things about the sorts of ways in which greater difficulties in the eurozone might affect the UK and those that might be more or less important to the fiscal position, which is ultimately what we're interested in. The direct economic trade links between the UK and Greece are not that great. So it's less the direct effect than whether it leads to concerns about contagion and the stability of the system as a whole and, crucially, what impact that has on the smooth running of the financial system and the banking system.</p><p>The concern is that you end up with an outcome in the eurozone that creates the same sort of structural difficulties in the financial system and in the economy that we saw in the past recession, and that that has consquences both for hitting economic activity in the economy, but also its underlying potential. And it's the latter which has particular difficulties for the fiscal position, because it means not just that the economy weakens and then strengthens again – ie, it goes into a hole and comes out – but that you go down and you never quite get back up to where you started. And that has more lingering, long-term consequences for the public finances.</p><p>What we did in <a href=\"http://budgetresponsibility.independent.gov.uk/pubs/March-2012-EFO1.pdf\" title=\"\">this report (pdf)</a> was to say, for what it's worth, the OECD has come up with a story of how things might turn out. And we looked at that one.</p><p></p><p><strong>And these figures [see page 177] suggest there would be negative growth for two years, deflation in 2013-14, unemployment higher than 10% and that the chancellor would miss his targets.</strong></p><p>That's saying what would happen if this particular novelisation that the OECD came up with last year was to come up. But the point is that it could evolve in so many different ways. For example, one issue would be do difficulties in the eurozone make it cheaper or more expensive for the UK government to borrow? If it makes investors more nervous about risk in general, it might make it more expensive. If they see the UK as more of a safe haven, it might make it less expensive.</p><p></p><p><strong>I suppose the question people really wanted answered is, how bad could it get? Can you answer that?</strong></p><p>Well, no. The problem is that you would be coming up with one story and claiming it was representative. I think Mervyn's view is the right one, that you can't say there's a 10% chance that things will turn out like this. What you can say is let's take a way things could turn out and look what sort of effect it might have.</p><p></p><h2>Reliability of OBR forecasts</h2><p></p><p><strong>That takes us on to forecasting. In your </strong><a href=\"http://budgetresponsibility.independent.gov.uk/pubs/Forecast-evaluation-report-2011.pdf\" title=\"\"><strong>forecast evaluation report last year (pdf)</strong></a><strong> you said one of the advantages of having the OBR produce forecasts instead of the Treasury was that people could be confident that \"they are based on (inevitably fallible) professional judgment rather than politically motivated wishful thinking\". How much evidence do you think there is that governments did rig their forecasts?</strong></p><p>\"Rig\" is not a word I would use. The key point about the pre-OBR regime is that these were ministerial forecasts and ministers were entirely entitled to forecast whatever they wanted. It's not as if they were fiddling the numbers. They were their numbers. Certainly if you look at the period for 2002 onwards, the then government published forecasts for public finances that the IFS and the National Institute [of Economic and Social Research] and probably the IMF and the OECD all thought were probably too optimistic.</p><p>Another concern over that period was also the way in which the fiscal rules were written. There was a concern that it was easy to move the goalposts in such a way as to make them easier to hit. So I would not say in the past there's been \"rigging\". But I think there is a concern that governments of all stripes have an incentive to produce forecasts that do contain wishful thinking about the future. The creation of the OBR was, in part, a response to those sort of issues.</p><p></p><p><strong>Is it your contention that having the OBR will create better forecasts? Or does it just create forecasts that are subject to the same degree of inaccuracy but people will …</strong></p><p>Think they're inaccurate for the right reasons.</p><p></p><p><strong>Exactly.</strong></p><p>That's a good way of putting it. You might want to distinguish between the forecasts we make for the economy and the forecasts we make for the public finances, tax revenues and spending and budget deficits and things like that. For the economy, we have no privileged secret information about what's going on in the economy that everybody else in the world doesn't have. So there's no reason to believe that we should be better forecasters for the economy than anybody else is.</p><p>What we do have is additional information about what exactly is going on with public spending, what exactly is going on with tax receipts. We're able to have more discussions with people at HMRC about what is going on with tax receipts. So, for the fiscal forecasts, hopefully we are able to use that additional information.</p><p></p><p><strong>When I posted a blog </strong><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/may/15/robert-chote-office-budget-responsibility\" title=\"\"><strong>asking people to suggest questions I should ask you</strong></a><strong>, I was surprised how negative the comments were. A lot of them [for example, </strong><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/comment-permalink/16133553\" title=\"\"><strong>Optymystic</strong></a><strong>, </strong><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/comment-permalink/16133907\" title=\"\"><strong>manzo</strong></a><strong> and </strong><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/comment-permalink/16138318\" title=\"\"><strong>hrwaldram</strong></a><strong>] focused on accuracy, with people saying your forecasts are no better, or if anything worse, than the Treasury ones were. On the key indicators, are you doing better than the Treasury or are you doing worse? </strong></p><p>On the fiscal numbers, on public sector net borrowing (PSNB), for what it is worth – and we've only got a couple of years to go on – our errors are by and large smaller than the average errors were under the old regime.</p><p>[At this point Chote produces a chart showing the accuracy of all PSNB forecasts made by the OBR since it was set up, where real figures are now available. The boxes are coded green if the error is below the average error incurred by the Treasury when it was doing these forecasts, yellow if it's in line with the average Treasury error, and red if it's worse than the average Treasury error. There are nine boxes: seven of them are green, one is yellow and one is red.]</p><p></p><p><strong>But what about growth? If I had asked the people who were raising questions why they thought your forecasts were so bad, I think they would cite growth. Two years ago you were predicting growth of 2%-plus in 2012, and now it's 0.8% and coming down. People look at that and say that shows you're just as useless as the Treasury.</strong></p><p>Judging that is harder because the numbers continue to be revised long after you think you know who's done a good forecast and who's done a bad one. That was very clear in 2010. All the forecasts we produced in 2010 under-estimated economic growth in 2010. If you go back even further in time, when I was writing about the economy for the Independent in the early 1990s, in the recession of the 1990s it looked like the economy had shrunk by 4.3% from top to bottom and it had ended in a double dip. That was the story I was writing on the national accounts of 1993. If you now look at the latest official data for exactly the same period, the recession is 40% shallower and there's no double dip.</p><p></p><p><strong>So do you think if the Treasury had been doing the forecasts in 2010 for 2012, they would have made the same mistake that you made?</strong></p><p>If you look at why growth appears to have been weaker in 2011 than we thought – and indeed I think that every one of the independent forecasters polled at the beginning of 2011, no one had anything as weak as 0.7, which is where we've ended up – the main reason for that appears to be the fact that there were pressures on inflation that were higher than people expected. Things like higher oil prices and food prices were squeezing household incomes, squeezing consumer spending.</p><p>[At this point Chote produces another chart showing the accuracy of all growth forecasts made by the OBR since it was set up, where the real figures are now available. There are six boxes: three of them are green (ie, better than the average Treasury error), one is yellow (in line with the Treasury average) and two are red (worse than the Treasury average).]</p><p></p><p><strong>You talk quite a lot about how forecasts are inherently unreliable. In your </strong><a href=\"http://budgetresponsibility.independent.gov.uk/pubs/Forecast-evaluation-report-2011.pdf\" title=\"\"><strong>forecast evaluation report (pdf)</strong></a><strong> last year you said: \"The chances of any economic or fiscal forecast being accurate in every dimension are infinitesimally small.\"</strong></p><p>That's certainly true. You cannot just say this is difficult, so there's no point even trying. Governments have to take decisions today that have consequences about what things will look like in one, two, three, four years' time. In order to take those decisions in a sensible way, you have to start with some sort of view about how the world is going to look if you don't do anything or if you do do anything. So it is very difficult, but you still have to do it. The key thing that we're trying to demonstrate in the way we do it is, don't bet the farm on any particular view of the economy turning out to be correct. And it's not enough just to say there's uncertainty around the central view that we've set out. What you need to do is say how much does it matter if we're wrong, and in what sort of ways.</p><p></p><h2>Relations with the Treasury</h2><p></p><p><strong>People have criticised the OBR for being too close to Treasury thinking. When I asked people to suggest questions, Polly Toynbee sent me one on Twitter which was: \"Why has the OBR been so wildly optimistic, when Keynesians predicted double dip would be the result of extreme austerity?\"</strong></p><p>And there's another set of views on the other side of the spectrum. We sit down, we puzzle over the data and the information and we reach the best view that we can, whether the Treasury agrees with that or not. Perhaps to my surprise, and to their credit, they don't come and say \"this is our view of the world, you agree, don't you?\" holding a large baseball bat up in the air. We all sit and discuss the uncertainties about what is going on. But at the end of the day the great discipline is transparency. We have to show our working. There will always be people who disagree with the view that you express. That's the nature of economics.</p><p></p><p><strong>Going back to the Treasury, someone on the blog [</strong><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/comment-permalink/16134197\" title=\"\"><strong>britannicus</strong></a><strong>] posted this question: \"Is it difficult to maintain an independent and objective stance on the government's fiscal performance when you are married to the Treasury's director general responsible for public spending [Sharon White]?\"</strong></p><p>The short answer is not at all. She's a career civil servant. So she's worked for the previous Labour government, and the Tory government before that. The jobs I've had have involved me being rude about all of them. It has never stopped me in the past and it wouldn't stop me now. Clearly, I felt it was very important when she got that job that we should be transparent about it, so it went straight up on our website when she was appointed and I made sure that the Treasury committee was informed before it happened just so that there weren't any concerns about it.</p><p></p><h2>Allowing the OBR to cost opposition policies</h2><p></p><p><strong>The legislation setting up the OBR says you can't look at the impact of opposition policies. But at some point they're going to review the operation of the OBR. Do you think there's a case for changing the legislation to allow you to cost Ed Balls' policies?</strong></p><p>It is certainly something that parliament should come back to in that five-year review. I said when I was appointed that I thought parliament should be very clear with us whether they wanted us to do that or not. I said if parliament did not give a view one way or another, I would talk about the implications of opposition policies.</p><p>The Australians are setting up a parliamentary budget office as we speak, which is very much focused at providing the research resources for opposition members to be able to go to this body and say: \"I've got a pet plan to change income tax, could you please run the slide-rule over it.\" If you do that it's quite expensive, because you have to have quite a lot of expertise in quite a lot of different areas.</p><p>There's a then even more dramatic example of this in the Netherlands, where every political party in the runup to the election is invited to submit its manifesto to our Dutch equivalent. The Dutch office is multiple times larger than we are, partly because you need to have more resources available to do that.</p><p></p><p><strong>One of the consequences of this system is that George Osborne will be able to stand up and say to the voters, \"here are my budget plans, they've been kitemarked by the OBR\", because he's in government. But Ed Balls won't be able to do that. Do you think there's an inherent unfairness in that?</strong></p><p>I think it's one of the reasons why it would be a jolly good idea to review this when the five-year thing comes up. When this debate was under way when we were being set up, it wasn't as though the government didn't want that question answered and the opposition did. There was no great push from Labour to say the OBR should have this role, partly, I think, because everybody was concerned that dragging us straight into the debate between plan A and plan B would leave you inevitably as though you were picking sides, and that might be very difficult because the body had only just been set up.</p><p>It's entirely reasonable for parliament to want us to establish our credibility and trustworthiness with a narrower mandate before you extend it in that sort of way. I think at the end of the day that having independent rigorous analysis of all the political parties' policies is a good thing for them, it's a good thing for public debate, it's a good thing for democracy.</p><p>You could argue that because the IFS does that to a considerable degree there's less need for that here than there would be in some other countries which don't have IFSes. But I think that would still be a positive thing. But it won't happen on my watch.</p><p></p><p><strong>Are you appointed for …</strong></p><p>It's a fixed five-year period. In principle I could do another five after that. I'm allowed to seek a second term if I want to.</p><p>But it's not just a question of people saying the OBR should do this. The government at the time would need to be willing to allow HMRC and DWP people to work with us in examining those sorts of things. I think it would be a good thing. And certainly from the point of view of IFS, the fact that we looked at every party's plans, and normally said rude things about all of them, contributed to people's sense of our independence and our evenhandedness. Partly because no party has the monopoly of wisdom or folly, so you normally offending all of them some of the time.</p><p></p><h2>Economic effect of cutting the 50p top rate of tax</h2><p></p><p><strong>Is there any evidence that cutting the 50p top rate of tax will be good for the economy in terms of promoting growth because it will make people work harder, or make people come to the UK to invest?</strong></p><p>We didn't think that there was a reason to adjust our medium- or long-term growth forecasts on the basis of that. That was certainly the view that we took back in March.</p><p></p><p><strong>Is that because the evidence is unobtainable? Or is that because that effect probably doesn't apply?</strong></p><p>Well, there's a size issue. When we're thinking about the impact on spending in the economy, we're looking at all the budget measures added together. And if you look at all the measures added together, it was a pretty neutral budget. There were giveaways and there were takeaways. But in most years, and on average over the five years, the takeaways and the giveaways pretty much wash out. So the budget was not doing very much to either inject into or subtract out of the economy additional spending power. The evidence on things like \"will this attract particularly innovative people who will have ongoing implications for productivity growth etc\", again, you would look at the size of the sums of money involved and at the evidence. Certainly, we didn't feel that there was a strong enough evidence base to say our long-term or medium-term view of the economy is now more optimistic than it was beforehand as a result of that measure, or indeed the other measures.</p><p></p><h2>Sustainability of public sector pensions</h2><p></p><p><strong>Let's turn to public sector pensions. You will have followed the debate about whether or not current public sector pensions are sustainable. What's the OBR view on that?</strong></p><p>We last took a view on that debate back in July of last year, which we will update in July this year. The view that we took then was that if you look at the share of GDP that you would be spending on public service pensions – we're talking about pensions for public sector workers, as distinct from the state pension – then that would, on the policies at the time, be falling as a share of GDP rather than increasing. So, looked at in isolation, it's exerting less pressure on the public finances rather than more.</p><p>That said, it was part of a broader picture which showed there was an upward pressure on the public finances. So, if you want to deal with the upward pressure in aggregate, you can decide whether to cut the bits that are falling by even more, or whether to try to cut some of the bits that are rising by a bit. It depends on whether you are looking at it in isolation, or whether you are looking at it more widely.</p><p></p><p><strong>So whether it is sustainable depends on whether you are looking at the public spending cake as a whole, or the public sector pensions bit of it?</strong></p><p>Exactly. But that particular slice is not where the problem is coming from, let's put it that way. That's because of linking pensions to CPI inflation, and the fact that you've got fewer public sector workers, implying fewer people you need to pay pensions to in the future.</p><p></p><h2>Tax increases or spending cuts in the long term</h2><p></p><p><strong>You publish a fiscal sustainability report every year. In </strong><a href=\"http://budgetresponsibility.independent.gov.uk/pubs/FSR2011.pdf\" title=\"\"><strong>the last one (pdf)</strong></a><strong>, you said the public finances were \"likely to come under pressure over the longer term\" and that \"in the absence of offsetting tax increases or spending cuts this would eventually put public sector net debt on an unsustainable upward trajectory\". What does that actually mean in practice?</strong></p><p>It's the idea that on unchanged policy the share of national income that you get in tax revenues does not really change very much as you go into the future. The fact that the population is ageing, and there are more people above working age than below working age, doesn't affect the total amount of tax revenue you get in very much, partly because older people are still buying things and they're paying VAT on them. However, if you then look on the spending side, that does rise as a share of GDP on unchanged policy, partly because, as the population ages, you need to spend more on things like the state pension, long-term care, health expenditure. That is where that pressure comes in.</p><p></p><p><strong>At the end of that report you quote some figures for what tax increases or spending cuts would be necessary as a result of these pressures, depending on what fiscal targets the government set. They're huge figures, £22bn, or £12bn. Do think policymakers have grasped the size of this challenge?</strong></p><p>The first thing I would say is that you need to place even more caveats around those sorts of numbers than you would do around shorter-term ones. The value of this sort of thing is painting a general picture of direction.</p><p></p><p><strong>But the government tries to save a few tens of millions by putting VAT on pasties, and the world goes berserk. And here you are talking about cuts of £22bn.</strong></p><p>But you are already seeing, not just this government but previous ones, talking about doing things about pension ages, for example. The debate about whether we ought to systematically link the pension age to life expectancy, that's a debate here.</p><p></p><p><strong>But do you think the public have woken up to the scale of spending cuts or tax rises that these numbers imply?</strong></p><p>It's hard to know with precision. There's been a lot of talk about the implications of an ageing population. I think people are aware of those sorts of pressures. The number of people who would give you a detailed discussion of exactly what per cent of GDP we're talking about I suspect is rather smaller. But I think it is something that people are thinking about and talking about.</p>","headline":"Robert Chote interview: 'I would not say in the past there's been rigging'","trailText":"The chair of the Office for Budget Responsibility talks about the potential impact of the eurozone crisis on Britain, the reliability of economic forecasts, and the future role of the OBR","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static