gle currency after June's general election.</p><p>The selloff was also prompted by the news late on Thursday that <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2012/may/17/spain-denies-bankia-customers-rushing-to-withdraw\" title=\"\">rating agency Moody's had slashed its rating on 16 Spanish banks</a>. Santander was hit with a three-notch downgrade, with its British arm downgraded one notch. Moody's blamed the sweeping downgrade on the weakening Spanish economy, and the Madrid government's own deteriorating credit-worthiness.</p><p>Santander UK insisted that the move would not affect its growth plans, adding that <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/2012/may/18/santander-is-your-money-safe\" title=\"\">customers should remain confident</a> that it was well capitalised despite the problems in Spain. In another blow to the Spanish economy, the percentage of impaired bank debts rose to its highest level since 1994.</p><p>The Spanish government announced that it will name two independent auditors on Monday to conduct stress tests to see whether its banks are strong enough. City analyst Nicholas Spiro, of Spiro Sovereign Strategy, warned that Spain was \"treading on very thin ice\".</p><p>\"The increasing risk of a Greek exit from the eurozone is putting even more pressure on Spanish bond yields as 'break-up contagion' starts to take hold. The downgrades are part of a drip-feed of dire economic and financial news out of Spain,\" Spiro said.</p><p>Traders in the City were in gloomy mood, despite the excitement of the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2012/may/18/facebook-ipo-stock-market-live\" title=\"\">impending Facebook flotation</a>.</p><p>\"The ugly prospect of bank runs appears to be spreading over Europe, rumours having hit Spanish banks yesterday to complement those heard about Greece earlier in the week,\" said David Jones of IG Index.</p><p>The FTSE 100 ended 70 points lower, or 1.33% down, at 5267. The German DAX finished 0.6% lower, while the N